Parliament did not support the amendment freeing Tymoshenko
Today, the Ukrainian parliament rejected the proposal to cancel the section on the basis of which opposition leader Yuliya Tymoshenko was sentenced as part of the amendment to the criminal code.
The amendment, which would open the way to the release of the imprisoned ex-prime minister, was rejected by the deputies during the second reading of the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for concluding an allegedly disadvantageous contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final, the court is to consider the appeal of the convicted in December.
Tymoshenko describes the verdict as a political revenge by the regime, the trial also raised suspicions of the court&#39;s bias in the West.
The proposal to drop section 365 from the criminal code, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 deputies during the vote.
226 votes were needed for its approval.
