France and the rest of Europe became the focus of investors
A statistical storm swept across Europe on Tuesday.
Individual states have published data on GDP for 3Q.
The Czech economy stagnated quarter-on-quarter, Germany and France are growing.
But the bond market is breaking records today.
Investors are no longer looking only at Italy, but also Spain, France, Austria and others.
The statistical offices of the eurozone, Germany, the Czech Republic and some other European countries have published preliminary estimates of economic development for the third quarter.
Germany&#39;s GDP grew by an expected 0.5%, France by 0.4%.
At the same time, both countries revised data for the second quarter, in which Germany fared better than expected (up 0.3% instead of the original 0.1%), while France reported a slight decline of 0.1% ( the original data spoke of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent year-on-year in the third quarter of this year.
However, the gross domestic product (GDP) stagnated quarter-on-quarter and, according to the CZSO, confirmed the trend of a gradual slowdown in the growth of the economy&#39;s performance.
The results are worse than analysts&#39; estimates.
Highlights:
In the third quarter of this year, the Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent year-on-year, but stagnated quarter-on-quarter.
The German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter, according to preliminary and seasonally adjusted data.
The economy of the eurozone and the European Union grew by 0.2 percent between July and September compared to the previous quarter, which is in line with analysts&#39; expectations.
The Greek economy shrank by 5.2 percent year-on-year.
The yield on its 10-year bonds is at 28.45%.
Italian and Spanish bond yields are rising to critical levels.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium, etc. are also starting to feel the problems...
Yields on Czech 10-year bonds remain below 4%, even though the situation in the region is worsening.
There are voices from Germany that the ECB should be the lender of last resort.
