An obese child&#39;s menu: he does not eat sausages for breakfast and dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9 percent of schoolchildren being overweight and 5 percent of children being obese.
At the same time, obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, as the current survey showed.
It is again shown how important the environment in which he grows up and the patterns he is surrounded by are for the healthy development of a person.
For example, sausages appear on the tables of obese children up to half as often as in families of children of normal weight.
It is no coincidence that more than 19 percent of obese people had fried chips for dinner the day before the research linked to the awareness campaign called Obesity is not a coincidence.
In fat families, it is also not customary to do sports, which of course applies to most families of today&#39;s schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children answered that their parents find time for active movement at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and almost 900 children from elementary schools from all over the Czech Republic took part in it.
It was already the second year of the event Obesity is not a coincidence, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand schoolchildren from 4th to 8th grades have participated in the project.
At the same time, proper nutrition and sufficient exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes the dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
&quot;For example, only half of the respondents stated that they eat five times a day in the breakfast-snack-lunch-snack-dinner regime, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition,&quot; reads one of the results of the survey.
Without breakfast and sausage in the evening
Experts point out that even relative details are important for healthy development, including, for example, regular family breakfast time.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of schoolchildren&#39;s families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone has breakfast alone.
And the worst thing was the discovery that a tenth of households do not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that unhealthy French fries are consumed much more often in families with obese children.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sugary sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly play sports, the result for their parents was less than half that - 15 percent.
Create your menu
The next part of the survey allowed the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own menu from the offered options according to their own taste and opinion.
&quot;The dietary preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition.&quot;
Their favorite foods include a lot of floury, meaty and sweet foods.
&quot;The great popularity of sweet sodas is particularly alarming,&quot; the final survey report states.
For lunch, pasta won just over poultry as the main course.
But the children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and vegetable midday meals is also low.
Leaning towards health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they receive the right information.
&quot;In the control group of survey participants who filled out the questionnaire after the educational lecture Obesity is not a coincidence, in many cases there was a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition,&quot; the project results state.
It was striking, for example, with sweet lemonades, where more children would start to prefer plain water.
Children also marked poultry and fish as the main meal of the day much more frequently in the questionnaire and would limit sweet foods and dumplings.
A stylist must also be a good psychologist, say the pros
In the introductory article about how stylists learn, I complained a bit that there was already a lot to do in the introductory classes.
I had no idea what would follow.
Lectures by three professionals from the field, dressing problematic characters and a seminar on how things work on the set.
And it will get worse.
The closer to the final exam, the more information and practical tasks await us.
And even though the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, it is really &quot;busy&quot;.
This time, the director Alenka and I discussed (there is not a single boy in the course) how to dress a woman who does not have a perfectly symmetrical figure.
And the vast majority are like that.
Someone has a short neck, someone has a boyish figure without proper curves, and someone is overweight.
A stylist must know how to optically soften wide shoulders, lengthen the neck or add the necessary curves.
We got tips on how to emphasize the figure nicely for a woman like Jennifer Lopez, i.e. larger breasts and hips and a narrow waist, and at the same time not to dress the woman too provocatively.
If, for example, the difference between the waist and the hips is such that the skirt or trousers do not really fit, then it is worthwhile to have at least one such piece tailored.
You definitely won&#39;t regret it, because perfectly fitting clothes are priceless.
You will feel much better in a tailored skirt than one that constantly shifts, rolls up, sticks out at the waist, etc.
A boyish character can afford to wear clothes with frills, applications, embroideries or gathers.
Of course, there is a lot of such information and types of characters, so I am glad that I have a whole week to organize all the information in my head.
And anyway, I&#39;m afraid that given the assigned homework, there&#39;s only so much to do.
Each of the course participants was assigned a celebrity, for whom she has to come up with two outfits: day and evening.
We have to take into account the current appearance, fashion style of the given personality and body type.
I will be &quot;dressing&quot; Miranda Kerr, you may know her from the Victoria&#39;s Secret campaigns.
I&#39;m cheering in my heart, for me personally, definitely better than such Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, who recently gained perhaps a hundred kilos (please consider the exaggeration), or the young Selena Gomez.
We have to cut out the clothes from magazines or look them up on the internet and print them out and then process them graphically.
Moodboard, as the entire result is called, then also expresses our personal style and relationship to graphic rendering.
It is also important to think about the graphic side of styling.
The stylist does not only dress physically, but also creates, for example, so-called product pages in magazines (for specific assignments, for example, trendy handbags, coats, etc.).
Stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about it.
But only on Sunday.
A stylist must have a general overview
Saturday&#39;s lecture, full of information about character types, was enriched by three guests from the industry.
Stylist Honza Pokorný, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and a stylist should be able to use it.
And a skilled stylist can work with one piece of clothing in different ways.
Variability is key here.
For example, such a trench coat (or, if you prefer, a trench coat) can be worn classically over jeans and a T-shirt as a coat, but you can also wear it on the bare body, put on pumps and take photos as a dress.
Or just roll up the sleeves or collar and the whole look looks different.
&quot;Play with it,&quot; he emphasized.
But I appreciated the following advice the most: &quot;To work, you need to know the rules perfectly.&quot;
&quot;Then you can start breaking them,&quot; said Jakub.
Finally, it is clear to me why we are struggling with all the lessons, what to combine with what, for what, why, when we sometimes see something different even in fashion magazines.
Not to mention the shows.
Thanks to the photographer Ben, I know again that a stylist must have many more options of clothes ready than the number of them that can be photographed.
So for a fashion story that will have ten pages (i.e. ten outfits), I have to be ready to &quot;stylize&quot; at least fifteen.
And also that in the photo the clothes look and work in combination with other pieces sometimes completely differently than in reality.
So we have to take that into account when creating an outfit.
Honza Pokorný confirmed to us that image and style sometimes make up to half of success.
Just look at Madonna, who is not exactly a miracle singer, but her image and marketing made her a world star.
In the Czech Republic, the approach to using the services of stylists is rather cold.
Even familiar faces sometimes consider it unnecessary (after all, it&#39;s enough that I can do something, the way I look is secondary).
And if someone already has us create a styling, then we have to count on the fact that, with a high probability, they will dictate to us a completely different (smaller) size than it really is.
Then all you have to do is google and find out if the tabloid wrote about the fact that the given celebrity gained/lost weight and the like.
On Sunday, both Honza and Mario told us that it is not enough for a stylist to be familiar with fashion and know how to put together an outfit.
In his work, he mainly communicates with the people he dresses, so it is important to be a good psychologist.
To be able to estimate people, not to condescend, to stand up for one&#39;s opinion.
&quot;When a manager commissions you to sort through her wardrobe and add nice pieces to it, you can&#39;t throw out her entire closet and say, oh my god, that&#39;s terrible.&quot;
&quot;Find at least a few things in there that you compliment and recommend what they can be worn with,&quot; says Mario.
He also specifically showed us what the so-called &quot;placovka&quot;, or bag for the plot, must contain.
It is the one that you fasten around your waist and have all the necessary properties with you.
In addition to the obvious things, such as scissors, a hair roller or safety pins, there is also nylon thread (with which the stylist helps when taking photos of products such as handbags or hats), special clips with which we fasten the clothes at the back if they are larger (pin or other clamps are not permissible, they would damage the garment), or sewing kit.
In order not only to listen, but also to try something practically, we learned how to properly glue shoes.
Even when shooting in a studio where there is a flat surface, the sole could be damaged, let alone outdoors.
And so we glued and glued.
We mustn&#39;t even touch the shoes with the scissors, so they don&#39;t get damaged by accident.
So it really takes skill.
Mario pleased me when he unreservedly praised my creation.
The aforementioned skill is really not my friend.
This is just a small fraction of what we heard about the second weekend continuation of the course.
It&#39;s becoming more and more clear to me that styling at a professional level really isn&#39;t a cakewalk, no matter what anyone wants to say.
In Need for Speed: The Run, you race across America.
Review
An initially carefree ride turns into a routine morning shift trip due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
Although the ambition was fulfilled to a large extent, it is of no use when no one clearly wanted to do anything extra.
The new volume, subtitled The Run, raised high expectations before its release.
He promised to take the old racing series Need for Speed a bit in a new direction, and from the playable samples it seemed like a game that might not be just a number in the action racing genre.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages in which the main character gets out of the car and runs around will turn out.
But as is usual with the NFS series, many things are a little different than we expected.
It&#39;s a potentially decent arcade race, but the whole thing is dragged down by a few unnecessary bugs that have been appearing in the series for more or less a few years now.
So these are not actually errors, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced to a story in which the main character, Jack, has some personal problems and the solution is to participate in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel on the west coast in San Francisco and your task is to arrive in New York first.
The idea carries with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is run on a different track and the given stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
So you don&#39;t feel for a moment that the game offers the same thing all the time.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it&#39;s nothing world-shattering.
But driving across the desert, autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains is visually very pleasing.
In addition, the races are from time to time spiced up with some atypical element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught up in a sandstorm, which greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are quite well seeded one after the other.
There are only a few types, but that&#39;s enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the required number of opponents (essentially a classic race), then you catch up with time again (a classic fight with a stopwatch) and then a duel with a single opponent awaits you.
The police also get involved from time to time, making your efforts even more unpleasant.
Passages outside the car are new.
It&#39;s more like interactive animations where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
But surprisingly, there are much fewer of these passages in the game than you would expect (specifically, maybe even only three).
In the end, however, it is to the benefit of the cause, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and, in the context of the above, it is thus classified as an element that adds variety to the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that it is certainly not much nowadays, but it cannot be said that it is a negative.
If you&#39;re looking for a realistic simulation, you&#39;ll have to look elsewhere.
But the driving model here still suits the more action-oriented racing quite well, even though we could find better ones from the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
But problems start to appear after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not very good.
We don&#39;t expect a game of this type to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but when you practically have no idea how your car will behave before hitting any object, then everything is probably not quite right.
Typically when overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic you will sometimes only lightly lick each other, but other times in an almost identical situation your car will end up in wild pirouettes.
Or even straight up.
Thanks to the system of restarts, it doesn&#39;t really bother you, but it will reliably upset you.
Restarts are handled in such a way that if you crash or go far off the track, the game will throw you back to the last waypoint on the track.
But there are only five restarts available in each race.
When you run out of them, you have to start the race all over again.
So it&#39;s more like a tool in case something goes wrong, rather than something you can rely on outright.
But sometimes even restarts do not help, they are solved only by the need to learn the given section of the race by heart.
The game&#39;s big ailment is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply cannot fit into them.
At other times, you will meet &quot;civilian&quot; cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It gets annoying especially in situations where you see how your opponent easily passes between two oncoming cars, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to go around them or brake.
It doesn&#39;t matter when you reach them, because it is &quot;calculated&quot; so that the given situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Opponents also have another advantage.
During the entire game, you will come across several places where, again regardless of time, the same opponent will always overtake you in the same place.
It hits the hardest at the end of the game on the long bridge where you&#39;re driving in the opposite direction.
The adversary must obviously get there before you at any cost.
When it drives in front of you, it makes your view of the oncoming cars worse, so at first you probably have to spread out a few times.
One can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-filled, but the execution is so obvious that it reliably bores you quickly.
And it&#39;s a shame, because despite the simple driving model, the gameplay is fun and sometimes so action-packed that sometimes you literally can&#39;t keep track of where things are flying.
And it doesn&#39;t really matter whether the concept with fifty unique tracks, the arrangement of the races so that boredom has no chance, or anything else is the merit.
An unconventional idea is to change cars during the races.
You have to watch out for roadside gas stations because that&#39;s where you can change your car, although in the vast majority of cases you&#39;ll be fine with what you have now.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American wreckers for straight highways and exotic super sports for technical riding, for example on winding mountain roads.
The main story mode also goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which is common to challenges and story.
As you get a higher driver level, various items are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with profile backgrounds.
At the same time, it is again connected to the online Autolog function, which, among other things, compares your results with other players and provides other community functions.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car, you get to the subway tunnel (maybe), where you drive it along the tracks in the dark (maybe).
The numbers between 150 and 200 km/h flash on the speedometer (so be it) and at that a subway train comes up from behind and ruthlessly destroys you.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a discussion for a few more days about whether nobody really thought at all when creating the game, or whether the authors really think we are such big fools.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
It freezes in such a way that in some of the more tense moments the shooting drops, and in some cases quite tragically.
But it mainly applies to crash events with a larger number of participants, when you would not be able to take smooth pictures anyway.
The sound side is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack from the &quot;every dog is a different village&quot; category was created, but it can be assumed that no one will buy the game simply because of listening to the music.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is thus considerably embarrassed.
If the game had avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work of NFS in the last few years.
But this is how the game feels unfinished.
It&#39;s definitely fun, but be prepared for the bugs to be glaring at you with the force of airport spotlights.
Choirs of the University of Warsaw will perform at the Velvet Students concert
The Festa Academica festival combines the celebration of the International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical experience for the third time.
During it, he will perform for twenty high school and university choirs.
The main focus of the festival are two concerts held on November 17.
&quot;Charles University has a big stake in the festival.&quot;
&quot;Among the participating choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and the Faculty of Humanities, Rector Václav Hampl will sit in the festival committee,&quot; said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organizing team.
The highlight of the entire festival is a concert by high school choirs, open to the public, which will take place on November 17 from 2 p.m. in the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
On the program is the composition of the famous Czech jazzman Karel Růžička Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, the &quot;Velvet Students&quot; concert will take place in the ceremonial premises of the National House in Vinohrady, at which university choirs will perform, including the choirs of Charles University.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the International Student Day with dignity and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music at the highest level to the public and develop the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organizer is the Union of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Jan Kepler High School.
The Mayor of the City of Prague, Bohuslav Svoboda, and the Rector of the Charles University, Václav Hampl, took over the patronage of the entire event.
The festival will take place from November 16 to 20 in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to festive concerts, the schedule also offers a whole range of musical meetings, student happenings, matinees and other programs.
Interested parties can find detailed information on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
Ambassador to the EU Vicenová:
Czechs have a reputation as negativists and Eurosceptics
&quot;The Treaty of Lisbon significantly disturbed the balance between the individual institutions.&quot;
“I didn&#39;t expect it to be such a hard war.
&quot;It will take five or six years for the situation to stabilize a bit, to calm down and for all the players to get used to their new roles,&quot; Czech Ambassador to the European Union Milena Vicenová began her lecture at the Faculty of Law sharply.
She showed how seriously she takes her motto &quot;Clearly and openly about Europe&quot; already in the first part of the lecture, when she managed to describe the individual EU institutions and their relationships in such a clear and comprehensible way that many lecturers from the Law Faculty of the UK could envy her.
Vicenová also praised the work of the new permanent president of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
&quot;At first there was criticism that he was bland, that he was a gray official, that he couldn&#39;t fulfill any role, and I have to say that it took everyone&#39;s breath away that he played that role excellently.&quot;
&quot;He is a person who knows how to listen to the twenty-seven member states, communicates well with them and has a clear vision of where the European Union should go.&quot;
She then explained the new post of High Representative for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy as an answer to the question: &quot;Who is the European Union? Which phone number should I call?&quot;, i.e. as an important step towards the unification and greater legibility of EU policy towards states such as China or India.
No one wants to ban cheeseburgers
Vicenová also devoted herself to the agenda that the European Council lived, lives and will live in the near future.
She described the previous Czech presidency as a success.
The Czechs solved the coming financial crisis, solved the gas crisis or organized a summit for the Eastern Partnership.
She described the fall of the government at this time as a big negative that severely damaged the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU is currently very busy.
In the words of the ambassador, not only the presidency, but also the subsequent financial crisis, which is still being solved today, was a &quot;fact frmol&quot;.
In addition, the new seven-year budget of the Union has yet to be approved, which is greatly complicated precisely because of the current economic situation.
Whether the budget will be lean and economical, which sectors will get priority, which countries will be supported more and which less, all this is on the agenda of the next meetings.
The ambassador also recalled her main slogans with which she came to Brussels: &quot;About Europe intelligibly&quot;.
&quot;I really don&#39;t like ugly abbreviations, foreign words, gibberish that no one understands.
How is a citizen to understand that curved or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes are not really invented in Brussels, or that someone really has to ban cheese curds.&quot;
He also wants to make better use of the EU environment and get more Czechs into European institutions.
A multi-speed Europe awaits us
According to the ambassador, Czechs have a reputation as Eurosceptics and people who notice the negative rather than the positive aspects of things.
In addition, she regrets the low representation of Czechs in European institutions.
According to her, many factors are to blame, for example the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational letters, but also low support from the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech presidency, she highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Four.
&quot;Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak approaches, the Frenchman next to me will say: &quot;Look, what are you meeting there, what about your Visegrad Four?&quot; and he doesn&#39;t look enthusiastic at all.&quot;
In the future, according to Vicenová, the Union mainly faces new tough rules for the budget policies of member countries.
He perceives the concept of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe, rather than a new &quot;European federation&quot; as very real.
&quot;We have eurozone countries and countries outside the eurozone.&quot;
&quot;We have the Schengen area, we already have the Institute of Enhanced Cooperation.&quot;
