Brand story:
The innovator IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were looking for a word that most accurately expresses IBM&#39;s strategy, the closest would probably be &quot;long-term&quot;.
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, and yet a hundred years have passed since its foundation.
The foundation of this longevity was laid by the first head of the company, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the slogan that many of the world&#39;s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His catchphrase &quot;Think!&quot; thus became the imprint around which the life of the future giant would unfold (and also the name of the internal magazine that began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson&#39;s carefully constructed corporate culture.
&quot;For us at IBM, long-term thinking means continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a century because it stayed true to its core values while not being afraid to change everything else around it.
This has allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope that we will be able to achieve even more in the second century,&quot; commented the company&#39;s current director, Samuel J. Palmisano, on the occasion of the anniversary.
A sophisticated system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the care of his employees in the same way as entrepreneur Baťa in the Czech Republic - people from IBM, as one of the first American employees, had paid vacations, insurance from the employer plus an elegant employee uniform and a sophisticated system for rewarding the best inventors and businessmen.
IBM&#39;s relationship with the customer has been just as elaborate for a long time.
From the beginning, the company was brilliant at extracting talent - as one of the first companies in the world to abolish any discrimination, so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisano to be replaced at the head of IBM next year by a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for thirty years, until now she holds the position of head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been doing so-called jams, online brainstorming sessions, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
It is not surprising that there are plenty of ideas - almost half a million people work in the company.
An institution with a good name
A firm position in business is ensured by its strong internal and external image.
&quot;From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than just a technology company,&quot; Harvard Business School professor and author of a book on IBM Rosabeth Moss Kanter told the Economist.
&quot;IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology,&quot; added George Colony of the consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between entering the market and directly creating the market.
IBM - or &quot;Big Blue&quot;, as it is familiarly nicknamed in the United States due to its logo - has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a hundred years.
It is probably the most versatile technology company - it develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in a range of products from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of any American technology company, and five of its employees have won the Nobel Prize.
Her inventions include, for example, an ATM, a payment card, a financial swap, a bar code or a floppy disk.
At roughly $220 billion, IBM became the second-largest technology company by market capitalization this year (after Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the tastes of customers and the times - for example, IBM failed to bet on its own OS/2 operating system, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers.
&quot;If your business is built on moving forward, you can&#39;t be emotionally attached to the past,&quot; notes Samuel J. Palmisano.
That&#39;s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on many platforms - and if they don&#39;t work, then abandon them.
Unlike competitor Microsoft, for example, which basically stands and falls on the Windows operating system.
Perspective technology
Services account for the largest share of IBM&#39;s sales, with software and hardware accounting for roughly a fifth.
At the same time, even in 1990, hardware was the strongest representative with more than half of the share.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-performing assets, while investing $58 billion in the acquisition of promising technologies.
It has continued to invest since 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world for the first time.
IBM is following the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to be coming through the current crisis unscathed.
Since the beginning of 2008, the price of IBM shares has risen by a rocket 120 percent, the company&#39;s net profit is continuously growing.
IBM&#39;s corporate motto is to change everything but your values.
It can therefore be expected that even if the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will handle it.
History of IBM: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally with the complex name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand used for the company&#39;s branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technologies such as the famous &quot;picháčky&quot;, i.e. clocks recording the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company&#39;s supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - an invincible corporate culture and identity are still built on Watson&#39;s ideas.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson was the head of the company, the turnover doubled to nine million dollars and the extensive expansion of the company to all continents began.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that, after almost forty years, his son, Thomas Watson Junior, replaced him in the executive chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, the people and computers of IBM helped NASA manage space flights - to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360 series.
The classic &quot;little one&quot; that set the computer standard of the time, called the IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, on the other hand, it bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to devote itself fully to consulting and services with high added value.
A strategy that has paid off for IBM in the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its goal is the smart use of technology in areas that have not even been planned yet and to improve the situation, for example, in transport or city administration.
For commerce, IBM recently introduced the &quot;Smarter Commerce&quot; platform, which helps merchants manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the country as well.
It established its branch in what was then Czechoslovakia as early as 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM CR, there is also a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central and Eastern Europe headquarters are based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team working on voice recognition.
