How tour prices have developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in what was then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies sold overwhelmingly only tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in the Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both near the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton) on vacation by the sea.
The clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia as well, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies also offered tours to the West, but you had to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or have &quot;good friends&quot; at the travel agency.
However, it was not won.
The so-called the foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for trips to the West, was not granted to &quot;politically unreliable people&quot;, who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the trip to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
By far, however, Czechs most often spent their holidays in their own country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that Czechs bought and this custom survives to this day.
Since 1989, Czech travel has experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989, holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to Croatia, currently the most popular for us, until 1989, as it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the visa requirement for neighboring Western European countries was abolished, which started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria&#39;s Vienna and Germany.
For a long time, Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West, everyone wanted to see there at least for a while.
For example, in Paris, tours of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of traveling Czechs at this time was to bring their own food, canned food, salami, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally freely buy Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with it average salaries were rising, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies regularly began to prepare tours with chartered flights from 1997, making air travel incredibly cheap compared to the past thanks to the possibility of contracting volume discounts.
At the end of the 90s of the last century, Czechs already had visa-free travel to practically all developed countries in the world, except the USA, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in the year 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first ever direct charter flight to an exotic destination was dispatched from the Czech Republic, to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters have been flying with Czech tourists to warm distant countries every year, this winter there will be direct flights from the Czech Republic to already twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs per year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the USA canceled visas for Czech tourists and thus our country was definitively ranked among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history they spent more than 15,000 CZK on one foreign vacation, including costs at the place of stay. CZK per person.
The general meeting is supposed to find a chairman, but there is a threat of stalemate again
Czech football has been without a chairman for almost five months and there is a threat that Ivan Hašek&#39;s successor at the head of the Football Association of the Czech Republic (FAČR) will not be known even after the next extraordinary general meeting, which will take place on Thursday in Nymburk.
