Jump into the blue
Julia Stanek
Paddling pool from the perspective of Ufon, a luxurious pool in Budapest: Those traveling in Europe can experience their blue wonder - and after sightseeing or traveling let their tired feet rest in the thermal spa.
The book will show you where wellness by the water is the most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a journey of discovery in the past year and a half, her luggage couldn&#39;t be missing: her swimsuit.
Lying prone on the water, she looked up at the artistically shaped domes, swam towards the marble putti (figures of a small naked boy, child (with wings)) waiting for her at the edge of the pool and admired the carefully restored art nouveau swimming pools.
If she liked a swimming pool, she entered it in her notebook in an instant - with remarkable details about the construction method and the history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools were explored in this way by the architectural historian Meder and she presents them in her just-published book &quot;Badefreuden (The Joy of Bathing) &quot;: Folk swimming pools in Munich, historic swimming pool palaces in the Black Forest, &quot;The hard core of concrete structures&quot; in the Taunus.
Her &quot;Journey to the most extraordinary spas in Central Europe&quot; led her through 13 countries: in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited locations in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and always one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia .
The 46-year-old German woman is a true enthusiast of swimming culture.
It doesn&#39;t go too far with sports, Meder says - it&#39;s just something else in the water.
It&#39;s just infuriating that amateur swimming has to settle for blue tiles and the smell of chlorine, while runners for health can inhale the intoxicating scent of spruce forests or listen to the cheerful chirping of birds in the park.
&quot;One day I asked why swimming pools always have to be so ugly,&quot; says Mrs. Meder, who lives in Vienna.
&quot;So I started collecting nice swimming pools.&quot;
The water surface doubles the architecture
Splashing in the plunge pool and essential oils for the sauna - the well-being factor is therefore so great that it affects all the senses, so much for Mrs. Meder.
And when the founders tried, swimming pools can be a real feast for the eyes: &quot;Instead of a floor, one has a water surface in the spa.&quot;
&quot;It is transparent on the one hand, but on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the entire building.&quot;
Everything is optically doubled: high vault, colorful stoves, diving boards.
The small-format picture volume &quot;Badefreuden (The joys of bathing)&quot; provides on 190 pages everything you need to know about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all it makes you want to jump into the blue.
The remarkable specimens were discovered by the swimming pool collector Mrs. Meder during her search in Hungary.
In addition to wonderful healing spas, such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Baths in Budapest, she found nitrate-rich water in an original karst cave (Cave Baths in Miskolc-Tapolca) and thermal baths whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are housed in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
On the other hand, many heated open-air swimming pools in Switzerland and Austria offer a wonderful spectacle. While one can see the whole city from the Zurich rooftop swimming pool, one can take a dip in the outdoor pool of the spa in St. Anton looking at the snow-covered Arlberg - a: There is a window in the steam bath from which you can watch the activity on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most striking pool design awaits spa guests in Längenfeld: the Ötztal Aquapark looks like a UFO that just landed in the Alps.
In the winter, steam rises from the three open-top basins, while the Ötztal mountain rises to the sky in the background.
The Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool did the smell of chlorine rise to the nostrils of pool collector Mrs. Meder.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, the Árpád Spa in Békescsaba, Hungary, smells of heating oil to such an extent that one can hardly believe that one has reached a medical spa.
