House of the 21st century in Vienna
Moved pavilion
Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural story with highs, lows and a happy ending: the Austrian pavilion from the World Exhibition in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, remained empty and fell into disrepair.
It is now being reopened as a show house.
When there is a clamor for modern post-war architecture, for clear forms, glass halls, bold expansions and new building materials, which are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer for the Brussels World Exhibition of 1958 is a fitting and famous example.
Schwanzer&#39;s pavilion received the Grand Prix d&#39;Architecture at the time for its light and floating structure made of steel and glass.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect famous by building the Austrian pavilion for the next World Exhibition.
With his legendary four-cylinder BMW-palace plus a turnkey secondary building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
The pavilion designed as a temporary exhibition building was placed in the Schweizer Garten near Vienna&#39;s Südbahnhof (South Railway Station) after the World Exhibition, reconstructed and opened in 1962 as the Museum of the 20th Century - it was named &quot;House of the 20th Century&quot;.
But the building was not suitable for a museum, neither spatially nor technically - there were no walls for hanging art exhibits, no suitable climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art got a new stand in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and deteriorating more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has reconstructed the pavilion, it is now called &quot;House of the 21st Century&quot; and will be used as a Museum of Contemporary Art in the future.
On Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the palace belongs, will open its first exhibition there - a happy intention in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, made a new start.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate art historian with a distinguished career, including a figure skater in her youth, later at Sotheby&#39;s, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modernity, strongly pushed for the reconstruction with politicians and preservationists, procured public funds and private sponsorship money and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba should be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a cafe and a bookstore should be created, and an office building had to be built for this.
Tight supervision, low budget.
Krischanitz was then the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he sensitively reconstructed and expanded Joseph Olbrich&#39;s art nouveau buildings in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an &quot;extremely important place&quot; for him, where he viewed exhibitions &quot;almost every weekend&quot;.
He knew the original project and he also knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness during its relocation to Vienna and change of use.
During the current reconstruction, there were far bigger problems: The building was a &quot;catapult for energy&quot;, says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, insulating glass reinforced with glass fibers was used, and the glass roof was replaced with special safety glass.
The cold bridges-steel beams were reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled ceilings were rehabilitated.
The two underground floors provided space for a new use, a recessed lighting channel between the building and the street provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - an almost new building, but still the lofty Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original entrance door has been preserved, the building is painted in an old anti-corrosion red-brown color tone.
And the movie theater is still exactly the same as it was before.
And all this under the strict supervision of the heritage office and a low budget.
&quot;Often, material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked by the heritage office,&quot; says Krischanitz, pointing to the broken basement floor.
Despite all the pressures, problems and renovations, the building remained flexible and airy.
It was said to be difficult with the pavilion, &quot;which came here from Brussels&quot;, said Krischanitz recently, a typical &quot;Drop-in-the-City-history&quot;.
Such architecture is said to be &quot;always in the wrong place&quot; and yet wants to &quot;instill proper self-confidence&quot;.
In this case, however, the House of the 21st Century is not in an inappropriate place, because an urban lucky coincidence happened: In the circuit around Schweizer Garten, a completely newly designed &quot;Urban Quarter near the Main Station&quot; with office and residential buildings is being built.
And perhaps there will be another happy coincidence: The 21st century house could receive support from another Krischanitz building, as the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berliner Temporäre Kunsthalle and is reportedly already in talks with the city about a site in the Schweizer Garten.
