The scandalous bank at Lake Zurich
Europe&#39;s most adventurous bank is not based in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS suffered near-bankruptcy during the financial crisis and has been sliding from one crisis to the next ever since.
Now some German has to settle it.
Axel Weber certainly didn&#39;t think so.
After his noisy departure from the leadership of the Bundesbank, it became known in July that he will start an almost equally spectacular new job in 2013: chairman of the board of the Swiss bank UBS - an unexpected and lucrative career move.
Axel Weber rejoiced publicly, praising both Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newfound solidity, and making friendly remarks toward future colleagues.
&quot;Die UBS achieves turnaround&quot;.
&quot;I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel&quot;.
But already in September it was clear that everything would turn out completely differently.
One UBS dealer in London bypassed all the bank&#39;s security systems and wasted around 1.7 billion euros.
The head of the board of UBS Oswald Grübel, a banker recognized not only in Switzerland, had to leave.
The chairman of the board of UBS has also been scalded since then - and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally come?
It has already become known that Weber has been allowed to advise the bank since February 2012.
And he will take over the chairmanship of the board of directors in May - not just in 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
It will be tough for Axel Weber.
He is not a banker, rather a professor of economics and an emission banker, and he would certainly need time to get used to it.
He will then suddenly take over responsibility for the strategy of the bank, which just once again proved that it deserves the title &quot;Bank of the biggest scandals in Europe&quot;.
Because UBS is huge on the one hand - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and on the other hand it has been sliding from one scandal to another for years.
Nothing, it seems, will be spared by the proud Swiss bank.
It started during the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS enjoyed an excellent reputation.
The image of a taciturn and solid but also shrewd asset manager is combined with ambitious goals: She also wanted to make a difference in investment banking.
Thus, in 2007, UBS managed, on the one hand, $1.6 trillion more money from wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, it advanced as an investment bank to the league of the world&#39;s largest banks
That made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later a long-time professor of banking in Zurich, recounts: &quot;At the time, I always presented UBS to my students as an example of a good bank.&quot;
&quot;Looking back today, one wonders: How could I have been so wrong?&quot;
He was very wrong.
In 2007, it first became apparent that something had gone seriously wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, the head of the board, Peter Wuffli, who until now was considered a highly intelligent and also brilliant banker, resigned surprisingly.
A few months later, it became clear why he had left.
The investment division of the bank squandered the Subprime securities and had to write off billions.
In order to withstand this, UBS announced a capital increase of 13 billion francs.
But she did find investors, but ones she would have turned her nose up at recently: an opaque Asian sovereign fund from Singapore and an Arab sovereign fund that was so discreet that you didn&#39;t even know its name.
But that was just the first bump.
In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to admit new losses of billions, the president of the board Marcel Ospel, 2006 still the second best paid board of directors in Switzerland, resigned.
In October 2008, disaster followed: UBS was on the brink of collapse due to its faulty investments during the financial crisis and had to be bailed out by the state.
Nationalbank bought tens of billions worth of problematic securities from UBS, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs in mandatorily convertible bonds, for which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken - because it noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to have such big banks on its territory.
After all, UBS&#39;s 2007 balance sheet total was more than five times the performance of Switzerland&#39;s economy (see figure).
&quot;Once again we could not save UBS&quot;, says banking expert Geiger.
The first disaster is followed by the second.
For several months, UBS capitulated to this in the tax dispute with America and showed a willingness to release the data of wealthy customers who, if possible, with the help of banks, cut taxes.
In addition, it agreed to pay $780 million - in return for unauthorized profits from these deals, including a penalty surcharge.
In doing so, UBS admitted more or less openly that it had facilitated tax cuts.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for wealthy clients: the halo of discretion.
After this scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was not what it used to be.
This was followed by the resignation of the head of the board of directors and the president of the board of directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Thus, the bank lost its credibility in the course of a few months in both core business areas: In investment banking due to bad speculation and in wealth management for helping to reduce tax.
And just when things calmed down a bit again, just when it was thought that UBS had recovered again, here comes this unfortunate business anabasis: A single dealer wasted 1.7 billion euros before the bank noticed that something was wrong.
And it&#39;s clear: risk management in investment banking is apparently still not working.
&quot;The Adoboli case probably shows that risk control has changed too little,&quot; says Martin Janssen, economist and Finanz Professor of Finance at the University of Zurich&#39;s Banking Institute.
The financial director of a large German bank is also sure: &quot;The problem with UBS is that it does not manage to control risks.&quot;
At the same time, it was exactly the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers stepped out a long time ago to become guardians of the world&#39;s great assets: no too great risks, but safety for money - the world collapsed again from this side of the Alpine republic.
Swiss bank vaults have become a symbol for unshakable reliability like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly high-quality chocolate.
UBS headquarters in Zurich still fits the cliché of a good Swiss private bank - it&#39;s just a little bigger.
The location is already classic.
The bank has its headquarters in Zurich&#39;s Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, shop rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers such as Tiffany&#39;s can be found here among traditional Swiss shops such as Sprüngli patisserie.
Swiss banks have been based here for centuries: from Nationalbank to Palast der Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Bär.
The UBS reception hall is entered through a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are lined with marble, in front of them there are massive leather chairs, next to the bank&#39;s logo there is a big sign to the &quot;safe&quot;.
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
However, this idea of the Swiss bank was sometimes suppressed or betrayed by the two big Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds out.
He would rather not read his name in the newspapers, in the end, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with both large banks.
UBS has probably grown too big, he finds out - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons have also expanded.
The Swiss probably have nothing more to say about it.
&quot;And if they did, they adapted to Anglo-Saxon ways long ago.&quot;
Indeed, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that transformed UBS, bringing it first high profits and then disaster: No European financial institution lost as much money in the Subprime jungle as Schweizer Großbank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster was obvious.
&quot;On that Wednesday, the government coalition of a small country of seven million decided on the biggest rescue operation in the history of its nation&quot;, writes the author Lukas Hässig in his book &quot;Der UBS-Crash&quot;.
Up to 68 billion francs, or approximately 45 billion euros, were approved by politicians to save a large bank facing bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see a problem mainly in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged into a massive concern.
A bank was created that was already too big for small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and it continued to grow.
It helped that the two different banking predecessors of UBS complemented each other: One rich but sleepy bank in Zurich with a focus on asset management and a poorer but more internationally involved one.
Suddenly the internationalized investment bankers had a lot of money with which to spin the big roulette wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, from 2001 to 2007 the head of the UBS concern, and Marcel Ospel, then chairman of the board of directors.
&quot;I always thought that Wuffli and Ospel were the team of the future,&quot; says banking expert Hans Geiger.
&quot;Wuffli, the highly intelligent, modest one who knows a lot about models and statistics and Ospel, the gut-guy guy who worked his way up from banking science.&quot;
But Ospel is said to have relied on Wuffli towards the end.
And Wuffli probably made a crucial mistake in the end: &quot;I guess he thought his models were reality,&quot; says Geiger.
“This is a tragic case.
Tragic, perhaps.
It is clear: Pride preceded the fall.
UBS employees clearly remember the meetings of executives, in which the head of the group Wuffli repeated the same slogan over and over again: Knock Goldman Sachs down from the throne.
Bank of America was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
It featured &quot;League Tables&quot;, a waiting list documenting the success of the banks of the time.
In it, UBS strove for a position at the very top.
She has already managed a few steps.
She was at the very top of the game in foreign exchange and stock trading.
However, the business advisers who were commissioned emphasize one weakness: In the international interest business, in the bankers&#39; parlance, &quot;Fixed Income&quot;, there is probably a big gap behind the biggest banks.
UBS probably has loopholes in US mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that nearly cost it its existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and the hedge fund it founded invested in US Subprime investments.
It developed into a massive machine that repackaged the securities into American mortgage loans and passed them on - while also retaining the risks itself.
Even when other banks were looking for a way out a long time ago.
&quot;Back in the summer of 2007, when the real estate market was on fire, UBS was buying there,&quot; says banking expert Geiger.
As great is the euphoria, so deep is the fall.
One manager after another had to leave as attempts to clean up proved more difficult than anticipated.
Positions at UBS became an ejection seat and are rocking to this day.
Whoever runs a big bank now has an almost impossible job.
They have to find a strategy for a bank that all nearby business models have disappeared.
Banking expert Geiger already has an idea: End investment banking, concentrate on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank does not want to go that far (yet).
But investment banking is to decline sharply, that much is now clear.
Next Thursday, the new head of the bank, Sergio Ermotti, wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Swiss-Italian was only seen as a temporary solution when the bank surprisingly parted ways with its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has established himself: He is to lead UBS&#39;s business in the long term, the Zurich bank said on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to bring the investment bank back to where it was in the mid-1990s.
3500 places will be deleted.
But that won&#39;t be enough.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does he want to earn money?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is already asking himself.
But so far he only says publicly that he and his wife will first find an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
