Smart crows are proliferating in cities
In many places, field ravens are considered &quot;problem birds&quot;: But these highly intelligent animals can no longer be banished from cities, say experts.
Some people like them, others would like to get rid of them quite quickly: Crows have been part of the image of the city for centuries, yet in some municipalities, residents complain about the dirtiness and noise caused by the animals.
At the same time, there is still no means in sight against &quot;problem birds&quot;.
Field ravens probably cannot be expelled from the cities, experts declared at the first symposium on crows in Leer, East Frisia.
There, experts from the entire federal territory consulted about possible solutions.
They are looking for alternatives in cities
At the same time, conservationists derived the problems of cities also from the exodus of specially protected field ravens: The use of chemicals in agriculture is probably increasingly destroying traditional areas for life.
Persecution, growing development and the felling of typical nesting trees make life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs are in Soest in Westphalia, in the northwest, in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and in Leer, among others.
There, a controversial 2005 mass crow-killing project in a rural district generated negative headlines.
Critics have described the trapping of animals in bird traps and the killing with sticks as particularly brutal.
&quot;Normal banishment, scaremongering, does not bring anything&quot;, so much found urbanist and landscape designer Werner Klöver from Leer.
Removing nests by spraying water or cutting down trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
&quot;Animals are retreating, large colonies are splitting up and dividing into other places&quot;.
Scaring is conceivable only as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
&quot;We have to live with them, we can&#39;t get them away.&quot;
The problem of cities cannot be solved without the surrounding area, was the opinion of the mayor of Leer, Wolfgang Kellner.
A combination of driving animals out of sensitive residential areas and attracting them to settle in other places is conceivable.
&quot;Information boards instead of chainsaws&quot;, on the other hand, was promoted by psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens due to a completely different treatment of animals.
Mrs. Jürgens co-founded the Ascherberg Educational Crow Trail in Schleswig-Holstein, where information boards provide lessons on the life of the highly intelligent field raven.
The project is said to have already been accepted by tourists.
Mrs. Jürgens also had her own opinion on the criticism of the noise caused by the birds: &quot;This is about every volume of communication, they have a lot to say.&quot;
The animals&#39; intelligence and dexterity are legendary: Ravens don&#39;t just use a tool to reach a treat, they even make their tool as a tool.
Researchers from the University of Cambridge recently tested the behavior of four field ravens to see how far the birds&#39; intelligence reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that the rocks had to cause the structure to collapse in order to reach the moth larva.
Without much training, they recognized what size and shape the rock had to be to cause the platform to collapse.
In the second attempt, the cunning crows then had to solve a more difficult problem.
In a vertically placed cylinder, the researchers placed a small container with a moth larva.
The birds could not reach their prey with their beaks.
But the researchers put pieces of wire there.
From them, all four animals fashioned a hook, using which, like a fishing rod, they fished the container from the pipe by the holder.
Three of the four field ravens managed to do it even with a jam.
