Carnage on a personal level
Peter Englund&#39;s emotionally powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a dizzying list of characters.
One piece of advice to keep yourself safe at that moment: Carefully tear this page out and bookmark it.
You will get to know all the characters very well in Mr. Englund&#39;s novelistic narrative, and this list will serve as a navigation - like a kind of beacon - for you at times when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in various situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as an &quot;anti-historical work&quot;.
It contains several well-known names, important treaties and famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, as &quot;a book about what it was like&quot;. It deals mainly with &quot;feelings, impressions, experiences and moods&quot;.
&quot;Beauty and Sorrow&quot; combines the wartime experiences of 20 or so men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go insane, or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of destinies while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund&#39;s book differs from classic historical novels.
It modifies the notion that the First World War was all about horrific trench warfare on the Western Front.
&quot;Beauty and Sorrow&quot; skilfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book deal with bees&#39; nests falling on them, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids, or dealing with the presence of tsetse flies.
It&#39;s a very moving read almost from the start.
War consumes people&#39;s lives like some natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina reeking of gunpowder.
When cannon fire starts in the distance and you are a woman at home with your children, do you run or stay?
Who is actually approaching?
Almost no one understands what is going on, or even why the whole war was started.
&quot;The vacuum created by the lack of facts,&quot; observed Mr. Englund, &quot;has been filled with conjecture, conjecture, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours.&quot;
&quot;Beauty and Sorrow&quot; follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are generally taken from biographies, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives can sound terrifying and engaging, but the inclusion of small moments and details makes them completely alive and believable.
Many of them deal with hardship and coping with it.
In the story of the German student, the author says: &quot;Substitutes, substitutes everywhere.&quot;
&quot;Coffee substitute, imitation aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons.&quot;
He goes further and describes meal replacements in Germany.
It mentions &quot;meat made from pressed rice cooked in mutton fat (and topped with a fake bone made of wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato skins, shoes with wooden soles&quot;.
It mentions that there were &quot;837 registered meat substitutes in sausage production and 511 registered coffee substitutes&quot;.
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds inner urges for savagery and brutality, and declares of war: &quot;Eventually you will understand that this is human nature. Not to sit in comfortable chairs with a cigarette and a whiskey, the evening paper or a good book and pretend that this mask of yours it represents civilization and that behind that starched self there is no barbarian hidden inside.&quot;
Conversely, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon and no one will even notice, let alone mourn.
&quot;When one finally comes to terms with sacrificing oneself, one would at least expect to do so in front of an appreciative audience,&quot; he writes.
Instead, however, he feels like a &quot;convict who will be secretly hanged&quot;.
Other notes concern the departure of old Europe and the onset of new horrors.
&quot;The conflict increasingly became an economic competition and a competitive struggle,&quot; Mr. Englund writes, &quot;a war between factories.&quot;
He captured what he calls &quot;a new kind of beast of the coming century: an eloquent and ideologically committed mass murderer in tailored suits who carries out his carnage without leaving his desk.&quot;
People behave completely unexpectedly, meanness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch some venereal disease from prostitutes in order to avoid frontline service.
&quot;The most grotesque example of this behavior was the trafficking of gonococcal pus, which soldiers bought and rubbed on their genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital,&quot; he writes.
&quot;The most desperate also rubbed it into their eyes, which often blinded them for life.&quot;
In this translation from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund&#39;s prose is brisk without being ostentatious, which suits his human subject admirably.
In dozens of small outputs, he captures the way in which the war &quot;unleashed completely uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred&quot;.
People are beginning to question why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
The best books about the First World War usually worked with hints rather than complex narratives, for example &quot;The First World War and Modern Memories&quot; by Paul Fussell or novels like &quot;Quiet on the Western Front&quot; by Erich Maria Remarque.
Mr. Englund prefers an unconventional approach.
His book has the most crushing ending, unmatched in popular science literature.
However, I will not reveal it to you.
However, you will feel as if the author suddenly jumped out of the book, ripped the page from the list of heroes out of your hand and set it on fire.
After the previous mistake, this time a precisely planned raid to the minute
It was attended by hundreds of police officers, some wearing the helmets used in street riots.
The night from Monday to Tuesday was chosen because Zuccotti Park should be almost empty at that time.
