Therefore, the police operation to clear Zuccotti Park of protesters was launched only after two weeks of careful planning and drills.
The leaders were inspired by the operations that took place in other cities.
A massive emergency response exercise took place at Randalls Island in preparation for the Zuccotti Park event.
Officials have stepped up so-called riot control training -- counterterrorism measures involving the rapid deployment of large numbers of police officers -- with a focus on Lower Manhattan.
The last part of the training took place on Monday night, on the Manhattan side of the East River.
The orders to move to the park came literally &quot;at the last minute,&quot; said someone to whom the action was initially explained as just a &quot;practice.&quot;
&quot;I know a few police officers who were also called to this event, and they were definitely not told they were going to Zuccotti Park,&quot; said the person, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
“Only the highest ranking members of the department knew about going to Zuccotti Park.
One reason for the secrecy was a lesson the city had already learned once.
On October 14, city officials had planned to clean up the park, but then backtracked because once protesters heard about it, hundreds flocked to the park before the operation began.
Police from various units participated in Tuesday&#39;s event, including task forces from around the area - dozens of officers who are routinely used to reinforce high-crime neighborhoods.
Mr Kelly explained that there were a lot of people coming and going to the park during the day, so one o&#39;clock at night was the perfect time to launch the event.
&quot;It was appropriate to do this at a time when there would be as few people as possible in the park,&quot; he said.
Emergency response trucks with arc lamps and streetlights lined up at the intersection of Pike Slip and Franklin D. Roosevelt Drive, near the Manhattan Bridge, before the units left.
The lights and the recorded message blaring from the street lights scared many of the protesters.
When law enforcement in their blue windbreakers entered the park, many of the protesters packed up their belongings and left.
Police say they did not touch a single tent until 1:45 a.m. to give protesters time to pack up.
Additional teams of police officers were seen gathering at the edge of the park to enter if any arrests needed to be made.
Reporters were forced to leave the park.
Chief spokesman for the police department, Paul J. Browne, claimed it was for their safety.
However, many journalists are of the opinion that the police wanted to prevent them from seeing its units in action, and that some of the officers were rude to them.
Mr Browne claimed that TV vans on Church Street running along the western boundary of the park could film without problems.
Police advanced in a westerly direction, weaving their way through a thick tangle of protesters&#39; personal belongings, including luggage and plastic bags full of clothes. Teams from the sanitation department set out behind them and immediately raked up everything that was left in the park.
Some protesters who refused to move were dragged out of the park. Documenting visual materials appeared on the Internet shortly after.
The most ardent group of protesters took refuge near the kitchen in their camp, which lay near the center of the park.
Some formed a roadblock and the police began methodically arresting them.
About ten people in the center of the camp chained themselves to each other.
And two people tied themselves to a tree, Mr Kelly said.
Members of the emergency services were called to cut the locks.
No arrests had been made at the park as of 3:30 a.m., Mr. Kelly reported.
The entire operation was completed about 75 minutes later, police said.
Mr Browne said around 142 people were detained at the park.
Most of the arrests were made for &quot;organizing riots and resisting arrest,&quot; he explained.
The highest-ranking police officer on the scene was Joseph J. Esposito, commander of the police department, the highest-ranking uniformed officer in the department.
Phil T. Pulaski, the department&#39;s chief of detectives, also personally participated in the operation.
Mr Kelly was present but &quot;was not involved in the management of the operation&quot;, Mr Browne said.
A second group of officers waited along the east side of Broadway, between Liberty Street and Cedar Street, in case it should be called out.
Barricades were erected on Cortlandt Street, a block north of the park, and Pine Street, a block south of the park.
From these places, the police then developed a protective belt even further from Zuccotti Park.
At one point, police officers, many of whom were equipped with shields, were seen pushing people even further beyond that line.
There were about 28 people at the northern border.
The wildest action of the night took place south of the park.
Around 5 a.m., one protester was seen south of Pine Street jumping on the hood of a police van and several others deflating the tires of a police van.
At one point, a piece of plywood flew out of the crowd.
At the end of the operation, one police officer and one protester were hospitalized.
