They point out that while there were no layoffs in Staten Island schools and only minimal layoffs in the Upper East Side, in Brooklyn, 17 school aides lost their jobs in Brownsville&#39;s District 23 and Districts 8 and 9 in the South Bronx even 46 assistants were dismissed.
He recalls that at Public School 36 in Harlem, five out of eight teaching assistants lost their jobs, despite the fact that it is a school where 68 percent of students live in poverty. The lawsuit says, &quot;This is not a neighborhood full of mobile parents who can raise funds to make up the budget shortfall.&quot;
Public School 36&#39;s budget was cut by 3.26 percent this year, and the school also lost money when the city changed the way it calculates bonus funding for each enrolled poor student.
Among other things, the union says high school principals may have been confused by the way the document authorizing the firing of parent coordinators was written.
