The mentioned sentences may seem innocent, but no debate related to Libya has been easy until now.
During the summer, lawmakers from both parties constantly argued with each other and with the White House over the wording of a series of statements to approve or, conversely, reject the United States&#39; military role in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain introduced a resolution authorizing the limited use of US military forces in Libya.
The proposal was rejected in the House of Representatives due to the differing opinions of the two political parties, so it was never even voted on in the Senate.
However, on the same day that this proposal was rejected in the House, the chamber also rejected a measure that would have stopped the funding of American operations in Libya.
Thus, the American mission in Libya literally found itself in legislative purgatory - Congress criticized the way President Obama manages the mission, but its members were apparently not irritated enough to stop supporting him in his actions.
In the end, other events overtook the hesitancy of the Congress.
Rebels captured Tripoli in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The Nato mission officially ended on October 31.
Now the Senate may be ready to act.
In a statement, the Commission on International Relations &quot;congratulates the people of Libya for their immeasurable courage and admirable tenacity in their efforts to liberate their people&quot; and &quot;commends the men and women of the United States Armed Forces and their allies who have engaged in the operation to protect the Libyan people , for extraordinary bravery and professionalism.&quot;
The statement also &quot;reaffirms the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya.&quot;
Will the new proposal get the full support of the Committee on International Relations, or will lawmakers again be divided in two halves, as was the case when the June proposal was approved?
The latest version was opposed by Sen. Richard G. Lugar (Ind.), the top GOP representative on the commission.
Lugar&#39;s spokesman said Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new proposal.
The House will vote this week on a constitutional amendment that would require a balanced budget, which should be the top legislative priority of nearly all Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
The measure, championed by Rep. Bob Goodlatte (Va.), would be the first constitutional amendment on a budget or other subject to be voted on by the full House or Senate.
For the time being, the other legislators have not yet managed to push their proposals through to the actual vote, despite considerable effort.
Goodlatte&#39;s proposal is just one of 68 amendments to the Constitution that have been introduced in Congress and touch on a wide variety of topics.
Some of them were the same - the same proposal presented to both the House and the Senate - and others are just slight variations of others.
In the House alone, there are at least 15 versions of a balanced budget amendment and another handful that would like to &quot;regulate federal spending.&quot;
Some of the proposals are identical, but their supporters - especially novice Republicans who want to improve their reputation - can boast of their &quot;authorship&quot;.
The budget control provision passed in August required both the House and Senate to vote on the balanced budget amendment.
In March, 58 senators voted in favor of a non-binding declaration supporting the creation of such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, several members want to discuss limiting the number of terms members of Congress can serve, while José E. Serrano (NY) wants to increase the number of terms the president can serve.
Representative Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Ill.) offered a number of amendments that would, among other things, guarantee the right to quality education and medical care.
An amendment banning same-sex marriage and an amendment banning the burning of the national flag remain standing proposals.
Some lawmakers also want to allow federal laws to be overturned if two-thirds of the states oppose them.
Although members of Congress seem to be very active in proposing various amendments, they do not deviate significantly from the average compared to previous years.
They offered 77 amendments in the 111th Congress, compared to 66 in the 100th Congress.
Their activity even pales in comparison to the early 1990s, when, according to Senate Library statistics, members offered more than 150 amendments every two years.
However, they were not much more successful than today&#39;s politicians.
The last amendment to be added - the 27th Amendment - was ratified in 1992, but was actually drafted by Congress in 1789.
