&quot;We are not victims at all,&quot; said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who commanded troops in Iraq and will soon leave Afghanistan.
“But it seems the only way some can support us is to cast us as unfortunate souls.
The subject is a very sensitive one for army commanders who do not want to appear ungrateful or spoil their relations with the public they serve.
They also realize that the wrath faced by troops returning from Vietnam was much worse.
As a result, most words of regret are spoken in silence and in private among war veterans.
When the two sons of retired Colonel Mark Canciano were returning from combat duty as members of the Marine Corps, their father warned them that their service would be viewed in two ways by people outside the military.
