Six months later, in April 2009, Lyman had a court hearing in which she was asked questions about whether she was making love to her boyfriend on the day of the attack.
Six persons were summoned to testify as hearsay witnesses in favor of the alleged perpetrator, who was ultimately acquitted.
&quot;I remember the day the verdict was handed down,&quot; says Lyman.
&quot;I felt like I was going to give birth right there - I ran out of the courtroom screaming.&quot;
&quot;They put me in a psychiatric unit, and when I got out, I remember telling my commanding officer, &#39;That wasn&#39;t his trial. It was mine.&#39;
The Lymans ordered her to see a military psychiatrist, who eventually diagnosed her with a personality disorder, rendering her unfit for duty.
In January 2010, she was discharged from the army without honor and therefore without the right to seniority.
Whether Lyman and the other plaintiffs&#39; case moves to the next stage or not, it&#39;s a long shot, says John Turley, a law professor at George Washington Law School.
However, he notes, &quot;From my point of view, they should be able to move on to the next stages of negotiations.&quot;
However, standing between them and the verdict is the aforementioned doctrine, which has been criticized since the first moment it saw the light of day.
I myself am a lifelong critic of the Feres Doctrine.
The military is several decades behind because their duties do not dictate maintaining the same level of incentives and deterrents.
He adds: &quot;The odds are heavily stacked against them... but it&#39;s important for them to try.&quot;
Change will only happen when good people are willing to fight.
