Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Are Examining You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who presented his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who pleaded guilty to the July killing spree that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he was certainly not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time on the computer while preparing the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After this summer&#39;s tragedy, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
&quot;We realized that it&#39;s actually not that hard to get them,&quot; says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently released report by a British research team on European digital populism.
Facebook&#39;s store of personal information is so vast, Bartlett says, that researchers simply had to use ads on the site to pinpoint the demographic they were looking for — something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett&#39;s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and targeted them with advertisements. However, instead of inviting them to a newly formed group or offering them some diet products, they were asked to fill out a questionnaire asking questions about their level of education, their relationship to violence and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever leaving the office.
&quot;It&#39;s a whole new way of doing research,&quot; notes Bartlett.
Some of the results aren&#39;t all that surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are overwhelmingly young men, irritated by rising immigration rates.
But on the other hand, &quot;those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.&quot;
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and policy researchers use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends hidden behind status updates, wall posts, and &quot;like&quot; buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them provides an average of three different data per day, which makes this social network literally an &quot;information supernova&quot; that is behind the development of many new researches. The number of academic theses with the word Facebook in their title has increased by almost 800% compared to five years ago.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the ability to study people without having to harass them on the street.
&quot;It used to be that if you wanted to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.&quot;
&quot;You would have to get to a side where they would never let you in,&quot; says Bartlett.
&quot;Facebook is breaking all of this down — you just go straight to them.&quot;
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid social-health problems.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that college students who discussed their drunken outings on Facebook were much more at risk of developing alcoholism than students who kept quiet about the topic.
Moreno suggests that students&#39; peers monitor the page and offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
&quot;You can&#39;t solve a problem if you can&#39;t diagnose it,&quot; Dimitri Christakis, Dr. Moreno&#39;s co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children&#39;s Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
&quot;We found a way to identify at-risk children that we would otherwise have no chance of discovering.&quot;
Facebook itself is constantly probing the data of its users.
The site&#39;s information team has compiled statistics regarding the connection between relationship statuses and St. John&#39;s Day. Valentine&#39;s Day, 2010 voter turnout, and the nation&#39;s satisfaction quotient (mainly using the information they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its trove of information available for research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is tracking them whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you have to give the site your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don&#39;t even know about?
Researchers have clearly defined rules about how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
&quot;I don&#39;t think most users had any idea that researchers could look at their profiles,&quot; says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, of a 2006 study he conducted using his students&#39; public Facebook walls.
&quot;As far as they were concerned, they took it as if the information was just between them and their friends.&quot;
Subsequently, there is also the issue of methodology to consider.
Even with offline research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way on Facebook to verify how much of the information on the profile and the posts on the wall are true.
&quot;What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things,&quot; explains Selwyn.
This is why Selwin, who has spent years researching new technologies, believes that the pencil and notebook remain the best possible tools to use in research.
&quot;When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, that&#39;s something that can&#39;t be replaced,&quot; he says.
&quot;Social research should be about society and social activities - and a hell of a lot of social activities still happen offline.&quot;
