7 lessons from the lost interview with Steve Jobs in the movie heading to theaters this week
As soon as Steve Jobs died on October 5th, opinions began to emerge from people comparing him to Henry Ford - and voting him the Greatest Modern Inventor for his genius.
In a recently rediscovered Jobs interview that was dusted off for a special film heading to theaters this week, it will be clear to all Apple fans that his creative mind had an absolutely perfect understanding of the business processes and workflows behind its products.
He was an amazing designer, dreamer and self-proclaimed member of the hippie movement, but also a meticulous organizer and a person who adjusts every little thing to the smallest detail - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffer from &quot;the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work... [ but] between a great idea and a great final product there is still a long way of a mouthful of work.&quot;
In 1995, Bob Cringely worked on the TV show Triumph of the Computer Nerds, which discussed the dawn of personal computing. A unique, more than an hour long interview took place during the filming.
By then, it had been ten years since Jobs had been forced out of Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company, NeXT, eagerly awaiting the general public&#39;s adoption of the Internet.
In the end, only a short part of Cringely&#39;s entire interview was used in the TV show, and the original copies of the interview were said to have been lost in transit.
However, shortly after Jobs&#39; death, VHS copies were found in the director&#39;s garage.
It is this material, slightly edited, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is heading to select theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who has a reputation for reluctance to give lengthy interviews, here Jobs seems surprisingly excited to talk about his technology philosophy and business strategies.
And he also appears to be a very thoughtful person.
Four times during the interview, there is a long pause between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thought, when you can see how Jobs thoroughly thinks the answer to be as concise and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs&#39;s perfectionism surfaces, when he seems impatient with Cringely&#39;s questions and pushes him to get to more important issues and topics more quickly.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, the interview is eerily prescient as Jobs assesses what other companies are doing right and wrong while offering his own vision of the future of computing.
It&#39;s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs&#39; career, but there&#39;s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here as an eager dreamer in the prime of his genius.
He has his own vision of how things could and should look like.
It wasn&#39;t long before, after expressing his ideas, he also began to put them into practice.
A quick summary of seven scenes from The Lost Interview that are definitely worth watching:
How he learned to run a business:
&quot;Throughout my years in business, I&#39;ve always asked, &#39;Why do you do this?&#39; and the answer has always been the same: Well, that&#39;s just how it&#39;s done.&quot;
No one knows why they do what they do, they never think deeply about business matters.
That&#39;s what I found out.
Jobs continues by describing his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was totally confused by the way the costs were recorded - they often started with the words &quot;standard costs&quot;, he could only guess at the amount. At that moment, he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that ensured that they could determine business costs in a matter of seconds.
How he grilled the Pope:
Jobs recalls the &quot;Blue Box&quot; he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make free calls anywhere in the world.
Much has been written about the device in the past, but Jobs&#39; enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an instrument of power is literally contagious.
He recounts how he and Wozniak tested the device using a pay phone, switching from one AT&amp;T network to another during a call while using as many satellites as possible.
&quot;At least half a dozen times we&#39;ve gone round and round the world like that, so when we yell something into a pay phone, it&#39;s answered a minute later from the other phone by the door,&quot; laughs Jobs.
&quot;We were young and we found out that we could build a thing ourselves that was capable of running billions of dollars worth of infrastructure around the world.&quot;
The two of us made a tiny little thing that could control a much bigger giant - it was an incredible experience and I think Apple would never have been created without it.
Jobs continues by describing a prank he and Wozniak almost pulled off. Through the Blue Box, they called the Vatican in the middle of the night and asked if they could speak to the Pope, impersonating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Gradually, more and more senior members of the Catholic Church were called in to speak to the American diplomat in the middle of the night, and it was only just before the Pope himself was woken up by the phone that the pair laughed and hung up.
How he fell in love with technology (and on the phone with Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and looking for parts to build an oscilloscope, he found Bill Hewlett&#39;s number in the phone book and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute conversation, Jobs had secured a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
&quot;She had an incredible influence on me. She was the only company I knew at the time, and she shaped my view of what a company really is and how it should treat its employees.&quot;
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company&#39;s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw &quot;the first desktop computer ever made.&quot;
It was the size of a suitcase, had a CRT monitor, and I instantly fell in love with it.
As a teenager I worked my way up through HP, hanging around that computer and started writing programs for it.
How they innovate:
At several points during the interview, Jobs talks about how he invents new products on the fly.
Early in his career, when he set out to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to put together an entire computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days at his disposal, during which he had to devise, assemble and deliver the finished device.
When he was later at Apple, he recalls the problems they faced in developing the computer mouse:
&quot;I remember we had a pretty wild argument... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a $300 mouse] until I got bored and went out and found a designer.&quot;
Ninety days later, we were able to make a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big companies run out of breath:
Long before he led the resurrection of Apple, Jobs presciently predicted that many industry leaders would falter in their vision and lose market share.
&quot;Let&#39;s say you work for IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what?&quot;
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can&#39;t be more successful.
At that point, sales and marketing already rule, so companies are headed by people who are in charge of just that, while people in charge of their own products are pushed out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius that led the company to its unshakable position is now replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
That&#39;s exactly what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could literally own the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times the size it is, it could have been the Microsoft of the nineties...
However, instead of winning, they earned a loss.
How he takes innovation as an art form:
&quot;There&#39;s still a long way and a lot of work between a great idea and a great finished product... and as that great idea evolves, it changes and grows.&quot;
You will learn a lot about him during that time.
You have to make a number of compromises - you just can&#39;t make electrons, glass, robots or factories do certain things.
You have to keep 5,000 things in mind all the time - different concepts - and put them together...
In the end it comes down to taste - you try to think of the best things that mankind has ever created, and in some way you try to reflect them in what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I&#39;ve never been shy about robbing the best ideas.
The Macintosh company was so wonderful and successful because the people who worked there were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and coincidentally, the best computer experts in the world.
If it weren&#39;t for computers and new technologies, they would have done amazing things in completely different industries.
Scalia and Thomas dined with opponents of the health care law while their case was before the court
On a day when the Supreme Court sat behind closed doors to consider the politically controversial question of whether to take up a challenge to President Obama&#39;s health care law, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, attended a gala dinner sponsored by a law firm that will participate in proceedings before the court.
The event took place last Thursday when all nine judges met to discuss the motions filed.
One of the cases discussed was a lawsuit brought by 26 states challenging the radical health care overhaul passed by Congress last year - a law that has mobilized conservative activists around the world.
The judges agreed to hear the suit. However, a 5.5-hour meeting is expected in March, the outcome of which will further stir up the presidential elections, which are scheduled for 2012 and will be in full swing at the time of the decision.
