And featuring guests? Scalia and Thomas.
It&#39;s nothing new: The pair of judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it is certainly not about anything that would be in conflict with the rules of ethics.
In effect, these judges are exempt from the code of conduct to which lower federal judges are subject.
However, if this were not the case, their behavior would definitely fall under principle C4, which states that &quot;a judge may participate in events organized by related and other organizations for the purpose of raising funds, but the judge may not be a speaker, guest of honor, or be featured on the program of the event.&quot;
Still, Scalia and Thomas&#39; relationship with the two law firms involved in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest in the case, was enough to alarm activists calling for ethics in government.
&quot;This shocking breach of ethics and disregard for the code of conduct flies in the face of several justices&#39; claims that the Supreme Court is held to the same rules that apply to all other federal judges,&quot; said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
&quot;Judges wined and dined at a social benefit with attorneys awaiting their case before the court.&quot;
Their presence and assistance in raising funds through this event undermines any claim of impartiality, which is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little sympathy for their critics, telling them that they too have no problem combining their judicial duties with the actions of groups like the Federalist Society.
Thomas&#39; wife, Ginni, is a high-profile conservative activist.
In addition, conservatives object that the ethical problem mainly lies with Judge Elena Kagan and not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was serving as attorney general under President Obama when the first challenges to the law came before the court.
Kagan&#39;s critics are pressing her to recuse herself from the case, saying she fought too hard for the law then to be dispassionate now.
