Europe&#39;s growing debt crisis has raised fears it could plunge the global economy back into recession, and calls have emerged for the booming frontline economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that all Asian support would be channeled through the IMF, but noted that bilateral aid - such as buying bonds from the European Union&#39;s Financial Assistance Fund, the institution for European financial stability - would give European countries&#39; Asian partners greater bargaining power.
Anand Sharma, India&#39;s commerce minister, said that &quot;India will do what it can&quot; to help the eurozone as its own economy now suffers from declining exports and drying up of foreign capital inflows.
&quot;Nobody wants the Eurozone to remain unstable and restless,&quot; he said.
&quot;We have a tough task ahead of us and we have to maintain a high growth rate.&quot;
&quot;This is not an alternative, this is a bare fact, because how else could we find employment for tens of millions of our young men and women.&quot;
Others argue that developing economies such as India&#39;s have no business helping European economies when they are forced to face serious economic problems of their own.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the US, said it would be politically very difficult to explain European aid to India&#39;s 1.2 billion people, when 800 million of them live on $2 or less a day.
&quot;One day they might find out that Greeks retire at 50 and enjoy their vacations on beaches, which would probably be hard to explain to them,&quot; he noted.
Lee Howell, director general of the World Economic Forum, similarly questioned why Indian reserves should be used to keep many Greek citizens in good-paying jobs in mismanaged and loss-making sectors such as rail transport.
Mr. Nag emphasized that the Eurozone crisis threatens a &quot;dangerous domino effect&quot;.
The bank&#39;s forecast of 7.5% economic growth in Asia between 2011/2012 now faces a &quot;downside risk&quot; due to the European threat.
He said vulnerable emerging markets must create &quot;contingency spending plans&quot; to protect themselves from a downturn and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Pentagon warning about possible defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta gave Congress a hard time Monday when he warned that looming automatic budget cuts could threaten national security and set off a financial chain reaction that starts at the Pentagon and continues across the battlefield in Afghanistan to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon will already have to spend $450 billion in budget cuts over the next decade, but now fears another $600 billion in cuts if Congress fails to reach a spending deal.
&quot;The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the entire resort,&quot; Panetta wrote in a letter to Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.
He said the inability of Congress to reach a budget agreement and the resulting so-called impasse will cause a 23% flat rate drop and halt many new projects.
&quot;Such a huge cut, used in this reckless manner, will make it impossible to do most of our building or shipping projects -- you can&#39;t just buy three-quarters of the buildings or ships. And it could seriously damage other modernization efforts,&quot; Panetta wrote to senators.
&quot;We will also be forced to furlough many of our civilian employees, and since the cuts are going to happen so quickly, we will also almost certainly have to put civilians on furlough in order to be able to meet the target requirements.&quot;
&quot;These changes could shake the faith of those who care about our military and seriously damage its readiness.&quot;
Eventually, the cuts will also affect combat units, Panetta announced.
&quot;Although accounts for financing possible military operations overseas will not be directly affected by this shutdown, operations there will be negatively affected by major changes in other budgets,&quot; Panetta warned.
&quot;There will also be cuts in contract personnel, which will result in delays in negotiated contracts supporting the war effort of our people.&quot;
&quot;The number of paid employees will be reduced, which will result in delayed payments to suppliers and the subsequent disruption of legal and political support.&quot;
Both senators wrote to Panetta 10 days ago asking him for details regarding the possible impact on automatic cuts at the Defense Department.
&quot;The consequences of the shutdown at the Department of Defense could cause a rapid degradation of the view of the United States as a world military power.&quot;
&quot;We are strictly opposed to this tough measure,&quot; the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they released Panetta&#39;s letter.
&quot;It&#39;s not a conclusion we can live with, and we certainly don&#39;t want to sign up to it.&quot;
&quot;The planned cuts are a threat to the national security of the United States, which we should not allow.&quot;
&quot;It remains to be seen whether Panetta&#39;s letter and fresh warnings will increase pressure on Congress to pass the budget and strengthen voices calling for the Pentagon to be removed from the cut list.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken in recent talks about possible cuts, even though he himself came to his top Pentagon post with years of experience passing budgets in Congress and the White House, so he knew he was in for an uphill battle.
At a press conference organized last week, the Minister of Defense gave a brief picture of what his department can expect - a shell of the army, inside which, however, the core will be missing.
“It will be like a ship without sailors.
“It will be like a brigade without ammunition.
&quot;It will be like an air force without trained pilots.&quot;
&quot;It will be like a paper tiger, like an army of barracks and buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to complete the mission,&quot; Panetta said at the start of a speech at the Pentagon.
“It will be like a unit without morale, unprepared and unable to match a possible enemy.
&quot;As a result, he will welcome aggression...&quot;
In an addendum included with the letter to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifies how the cuts will result in &quot;significant operational risks: delayed response to crises, conflicts and disasters; significant reductions in airborne and deployment capabilities worldwide; projected unacceptable risk in future combat operations.&quot;
In addition, Panetta added that some of the largest defense projects could face termination, including those that are already being tested and those that are only in the early stages of planning.
The list included, for example, the F35 project, a planned new bomber, a next-generation ballistic submarine, a new littoral combat ship and a new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Marine Corps wanted to replace the Humvee with.
Halting further development and testing of the F35 would save $80 billion over the next 10 years, but supporters say it is a necessary next step in upgrading the military, which is needed for the country to deal with potential threats from China and other rivals .
How to spot a lie
A cursory glance at recent newspaper headlines suggests just how serious and pervasive lies and deception are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain has his hands full amid allegations that he sexually harassed multiple women -- both sides say the other is lying.
Administrators at Penn State University have been accused of perjury when they tried to cover up records that a retired football coach sexually assaulted a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling US President Barack Obama into a microphone that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie was able to destroy entire careers and undermine the stability of many countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of misusing campaign funds to try to hide his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that erupted around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual affair with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating at school and university abound.
There are cases where teachers themselves will give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite send the message that lying and cheating is acceptable.
How many scams do we encounter?
Studies show that you lie anywhere between 10 and 200 times in a single day.
Suppose many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first meeting.
Lie detection, or &quot;lie detection&quot;, is an essential skill that everyone should learn, whether for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a party game similar to, say, Charades where one shouts &quot;I got you&quot;. Deception detection is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities in the course of detailed research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and philosophy.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you straight in the eye.
It&#39;s not like they stammer, stutter, blush, or fidge.
However, do not assume that it is somehow difficult to spot and detect liars.
A trained lie detector can detect the truth from sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are phrased and their timing.
I&#39;ve spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from the vast and growing field of lie detection, and it&#39;s clear that deception detection is a modern skill that&#39;s easy to learn and can be of great help in today&#39;s complex world - especially if your job duties include include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing people.
Good liars are also good at reading others, letting them down, channeling their emotions and intuitively realizing how the other side is receiving them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more &quot;self-centered&quot; lies, while women tell more &quot;other-centered&quot; lies - mostly to protect someone&#39;s feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (however, the lies they tell are usually &quot;outrageous&quot;).
We also know that if you are seen as a sinner, others feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know someone is lying?
First, observe the subject&#39;s normal behavior.
This is called an &quot;initial observation&quot;.
Thanks to it, later findings will have something to compare with.
Notice the subject&#39;s posture, his laughter, voice work.
You should know if someone habitually taps their feet all the time so that you don&#39;t falsely accuse them of lying just because they start tapping their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of fake verbal and non-verbal behavior.
However, take these only as warning signs, not as proof of a lie.
People who tell lies may stop moving their upper body as they try to recall their fabricated story, turn their toes toward the door, lean toward the exit, change their posture significantly, or show &quot;relief when the conversation is over&quot;—exaggerated sighs of relief and change positions when a difficult confession is behind them.
Interviewers will often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what the relief will look like when it is over.
Also note the subject&#39;s language.
There is a famous story about how Scott Peterson once misspoken and used the past tense when he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, sparking a nationwide manhunt for her body.
Lying individuals may also say measuredly: &quot;I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinska&quot; or repeat the difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal signs are very slight.
Someone can use a lot of &quot;mitigating language&quot; when answering a difficult question: &quot;Well... to tell you the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge.&quot;
We don&#39;t learn too many facts in such an answer and it is often another warning signal.
There is no magic that can detect every lie, but it is possible to learn the skills to spot a lie.
With the help of these skills, a person will have a better chance of not encountering a liar and a fraud in his personal and professional life.
Controversial oil pipeline plan to be redirected after US government approval threatened to be delayed
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned oil pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico - antagonizing unions but reassuring environmentalists - the company building the pipeline said it was willing to redirect the project so that things are moving again.
TransCanada announced Monday night that it will move the pipeline&#39;s planned route out of the environmentally sensitive Sandhills region of Nebraska, and is confident the project will be approved anyway.
The company announced the decision at a news conference at the Nebraska State Capitol.
TransCanada columnist Alex Pourbax says the company is confident the pipeline will eventually be approved, even though it will take a different route.
The announcement came after the State Department announced last week that it was delaying a decision on a federal permit for the project, pending studies of possible alternate routes that would avoid impacting Nebraska&#39;s Sandhills region and the Ogallala Aquifer, a vast underground reservoir of water.
&quot;This is really a step forward,&quot; Republican Representative Lee Terry of Nebraska told Fox News.
A new environmental assessment commissioned by the State Department would likely delay any decision until 2013, a year after next year&#39;s election, but authorities deny that politics played any role in the decision.
In a written statement last week, Obama described the decision as a State Department request and expressed his support for it.
The 1,700-mile pipeline will connect Canada and the Gulf of Mexico.
700,000 barrels of oil flow daily from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
This route will have to cross 6 states.
The project is absolutely loathed by environmentalists, but loved by work crews who estimate that 20,000 new jobs will be created by the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers have opposed the plan and are considering laws that would force the company to stay out of the Sand Hills region and the Ogallala Aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
An existing State Department-commissioned environmental impact study found the project would have only a minor negative environmental impact, but an energy industry source said the department&#39;s inspector general has ordered a new review of the entire original study process, focusing mainly on two questions.
One was whether a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was an adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, presented a conflict of interest in the program.
Another is whether the firm that was hired to do the original study was improperly chosen because it had ties to TransCanada.
