The adverse climate slowed down the economy
During the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment decreased and with it the economy
The year 2011 will go down in Sinaloa&#39;s economic history. This is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, which calls itself the government of change. This government brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to unfavorable climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth and even a decline in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February caused millions of dollars in losses in agriculture, limited the growth opportunities of the state economy, and are responsible for the reduction of economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. In the field of agriculture, there was a historic decline of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors as well.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78.03% was completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% was partially damaged. The main crops destroyed include vegetables, maize and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state has seen an increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 residents of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment rose to 5.28%, and between July and August, average unemployment continued to rise to 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed. Compared to the first quarter, the number of unemployed increased by 18,969 people.
Less liquidity
Several factors are responsible for unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa. According to Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, it is possible to explain the increase in unemployment indirectly, based on the steps that have been taken at the level of public policy.
&quot;We are witnessing rising unemployment that is related to various factors. These include, but are not limited to, the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints as a result of the anti-money laundering legislation passed by Congress. For people who illegally get their hands on dollars, it is not easy for them to earn it, invest it or use it for something,&quot; he emphasized.
Stop migration
López Cervantes said that the demographic factor is also involved in the increase in unemployment.
&quot;The number of people going to work abroad, to the United States, has decreased, both because of the difficulty of entry and also because even when these people get across the border, it is difficult for them to find work. So people stay and they demand work from our state, so unemployment is growing&quot;, he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa also worsens due to the increasing unreliability that prevails in the field of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed population in the state work without paying benefits to the social security administration.
Unemployment and unreliability are compounded by other features of the labor market, such as low wages. This administrative territory has the lowest salaries in the whole country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa state was 5,352 pesetas as of September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesetas.
Shortening foreign direct investment
Together with the decrease in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, 2011 also saw the most significant decrease in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years. According to the Ministry of Finance, in the period from January to June, foreign direct investment reached the amount of 630,697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74% compared to the amount of 5,143,312 dollars for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government reports investments of 17,280 million pesetas per year. These investments were mainly aimed at companies in the service sector.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government of this state asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos. This would be intended for investments in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas with the aim of revitalizing the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. By November, there were no gains on debt, in any sector of the state economy.
Reaction
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés highlighted the lack of management skills of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, stated that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the state government itself.
&quot;The development of the economy in Sinaloa has been really slight during this year. We have to work intensively to regain the ground we lost this year. In 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, there was a lack of harmonization of the efforts of all of us and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better,&quot; he said.
Slow economy
Loredo López said that events such as frost at the beginning of the year halted the state&#39;s economy and limited its development and growth.
&quot;The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to re-establish the dynamism that would allow to reach an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. That is why we are at at the end of the year they found themselves well below the expected forecasts&quot;, he said.
Redefining the mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed towards more dynamic productive activities.
&quot;Generally speaking, we observe that work is being done. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared, in which the goals and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important to mobilize all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has&quot;. he said.
The work ahead
The Coparmex chairman emphasized the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better guide the government&#39;s efforts.
&quot;In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, there has been some progress in the area of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan&quot;, he said.
He said the current administration has shown progress in conducting public policy.
&quot;There are elements that make it possible to say that the government is trying to be welcoming. I can say that the work done here is visible, and I believe that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead,&quot; he said.
