Court approves &quot;end of analog broadcasting&quot; in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital ones is one of the most important changes that the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuit presented by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which wants to speed up the so-called &quot;switching off of analog signals&quot; and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021. It stated that the necessary eight votes that would invalidate it were not found.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree outlining the steps that will lead to the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed, because the qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the said decree, which thus remains valid, was not reached.
The draft judgment drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero presents the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, since the regulation of all matters relating to radio and television is a matter reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel). Thus, there is a violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the exception of the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an attempt to fight the decree. Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the implementation of the decree and all the actions described in it, leading to the transition to digitalization.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he does not agree with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure measures through general standards to prepare the public administration.
&quot;I don&#39;t think that even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body&quot;, recalling that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital ones is one of the biggest changes that the world has experienced in recent years. It is related to better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He believes that delaying change would mean delaying the benefits of digitization, which requires a decision in the public interest. Digitization does not only have a technical dimension, but &quot;also affects economic, social, political and national security issues&quot;.
As he emphasized, these issues &quot;require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the state. It includes a whole range of competences that the Constitution entrusts to the hands of the state government&quot;.
He recalled that a number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to a digital system and had done so through their governments, despite having highly specialized technical authorities at their disposal.
He stated that it was not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree which encroached to some extent upon the powers of Congress, to bring into the domain of administration the observance of the laws prepared by the legislature.
In Michoacán, they are analyzing the possibility of a vote-by-vote census
According to data released by PREP, the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is less than 27 percent. The votes of 879 of the 6,074 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
The vote-by-vote counting option appeared in this year&#39;s elections in Michoacán, where, according to data released by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is less than 27 percent, and that&#39;s not counting the votes of 879 of a total of 6074 electoral districts.
In this context, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of measures that should harmonize local norms with the federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán has not officially ratified its political constitution or its State Electoral Code or Law on Electoral Justice. Indeed, the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force this election period was to expire, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel neglected to publish them within the deadline set in the Official State Gazette Law, saying that he had some objections to them.
On November 9, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) resolved a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislative power and declared the head of state&#39;s vote on constitutional reforms &quot;invalid and illegal&quot; because he has no right to &quot;neither approve nor veto&quot; them.
When asked about the possibility of a vote-by-vote count, María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the IEM General Council, it would be possible for the local electoral body to carry out partial and total counts.
In this way, a partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, will be possible under the following conditions: the election results do not agree; there is no record of the counting of votes and the calculation in the relevant box or it is not available to the chairman in question; or if there were errors and obvious violations of the election results.
In addition, a total recount of votes in all ballot boxes will be possible if there is an indication that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever there is an express request at the beginning of the session by a representative of the party and/or coalition that proposed the candidate in second place.
A total recount of votes will also be possible if, after a proper count, it is found that the difference between the likely winner and the runner-up is equal to or less than one percentage point, and also whenever there is an express request of the political party whose candidate finished in second place. In such a case, electoral parcels for which a partial count was carried out will be discarded.
It should be mentioned that the election in Morelia is in such a situation, where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is less than 0.16%, even though 129 of the total 923 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
His last will
