A new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet the Italian president tomorrow to present him with a new government to tackle the crisis that is keeping the country on the brink of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet Italy&#39;s president tomorrow to present him with a new government to tackle the crisis that is keeping the country on the brink of economic disaster and has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The presidential palace issued a statement announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
He is expected to introduce a government made up mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
&quot;I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country&#39;s ability to overcome this difficult phase,&quot; the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles had been overcome.
&quot;The framework is now well defined&quot;, he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much shorter than usual. Meanwhile, Italy struggles to combat a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package demanded by European leaders. Only in this way will it be possible to restore Italy&#39;s shattered credibility.
There is a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry up. Because of market volatility, interest on Italy&#39;s 10-year BTP bonds exceeded 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for a bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers&#39; organization Confindustria, told reporters after the meeting with Monti: &quot;We said we will support this government very much&quot;.
We believe that this government is the last option to get Italy out of this burning situation.
Monti&#39;s hopes of success have been greatly boosted by the PDL&#39;s support for Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday by the crisis.
&quot;We believe that Professor Monti&#39;s efforts are destined for good results,&quot; Angelina Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy&#39;s largest party, is significant because until now many of its members have opposed Monti&#39;s technocratic majority government.
Parliament support
Monti&#39;s new government must have strong parliamentary support to push through unpopular austerity reforms.
Any setback or delay in that effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti&#39;s failure could spell disaster.
On Monday, Monti opened negotiations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women&#39;s organizations.
The round of negotiations will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, who has enabled a very rapid response to the crisis.
After a brief decline at the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond yields have returned to a critical level, reacting to uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Saving Italy, whose public debt stands at 1.8 trillion euros, would be beyond the means of the eurozone&#39;s current financial reserves.
Monti has said his government should stay in power until the next election, which is scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that say politicians will only give him time to implement reforms and then call early elections .
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that this government must be made up of experts only to lead Italy out of the trouble the country has been in due to financial pressure.
Political sources said that mutual mistrust and disagreement between the parties complicates the attempt to include political figures in the government.
