The quintet included the country in their tour to celebrate twenty years of existence
&quot;A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true&quot;
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said that the group is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We&#39;ve been waiting for more than 20 years, but the band itself assures that the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true for them.
So said bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively to Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate twenty years of existence and will make a unique stop in Central America on Sunday the 20th.
On this day, he will perform from 19:30 at the National Stadium together with the angel group The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the interview, the full transcript of which can be found on La Nación&#39;s website.
It&#39;s a dream come true for your Costa Rican supporters. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
A trip to Costa Rica is also our dream that is becoming a reality.
This is only our second time in South and Central America and the experience so far has been great.
I&#39;ve only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It is a beautiful country and I believe we will be able to stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to bring you our music.
I ask because they literally adore the group here, the fans experience these preparation days very intensely.
What do you say to your staunchest supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry it took us so long.
Some people are already talking about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we&#39;ve put on in the last 21 years have been created in the space of a few weeks.
We played some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope to get ourselves in shape for the gig in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surfable waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. And that&#39;s how we found out about Costa Rica, through people who love to surf.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What do you have planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we&#39;ve never played here, there&#39;s no limit to what we can&#39;t do.
We will try to put on the best show possible with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and varied repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why?
I think part of it is because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it&#39;s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven&#39;t played for a long time, we focus on them and are also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have already forgotten about it.
That makes the show more interesting for us, and that&#39;s why I think it&#39;s more interesting for people.
With this tour you are celebrating 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, is it hard to believe all you accomplished?
Yes, that&#39;s for sure.
First of all, I don&#39;t think any of us could have imagined that we would be in one big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years. That sounds like a dream.
We realize how much has been given to us and are touched that we can continue to play together.
We like each other and we like making music.
We are lucky to be able to see the places we have always wanted to see.
We couldn&#39;t have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which the greats themselves are represented.
The people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It&#39;s surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn&#39;t happen very often.
From time to time a group will form in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at once.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play with some.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky to have all of them as our friends and honored to be a part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It&#39;s also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a lot longer than the usual duration of a band.
I think that firstly, we are all lucky to still be in this world and secondly, the fact that we are always interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to that we have managed to open musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we respect each other&#39;s music and I think it couldn&#39;t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame was not simple. However, thanks to your success, you can do whatever you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it gradually became easier to find the balance.
We try not to tour too much because it&#39;s very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for the music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You mustn&#39;t get carried away by being famous, rock stars. Neither of us ever really cared.
How do you remember Mother Love Bone&#39;s next project?
I think we wrote great songs and it was something spectacular at the beginning.
We were a band for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. Most importantly, we are still friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at photos, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, laugh, talk about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you&#39;re familiar with their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that&#39;s why you chose them as frontmen?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several designs and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious to see what Las Robertas will offer live and they must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That&#39;s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don&#39;t know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
A lot of people.
The first ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, CJ Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge going even though it&#39;s out of style?
I think we&#39;ve all always felt slightly detached from the word grunge.
When I say grunge, I think of the bands I mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out at the same time. And if the music is still valid like that today, that&#39;s a great thing, because it&#39;s music worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly gloomy character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
It&#39;s interesting because I feel like there are a few songs on the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very dark, even though they can sound positive.
Both of them made me cry when Ed played them, and they&#39;re deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and have some kind of trauma in your life, lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
