Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized on Tuesday at a public hospital where he will undergo tests due to muscle loss in his lower limbs, his attending physician said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights abuses committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four operations and is currently under control by doctors.
Rep. Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told Canal N television that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases in three days to find out why he is in pain and losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned on humanitarian grounds, however, the former president himself does not want a pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and added to these problems were other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst on the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulation problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a killing squad of troops operating illegally in the first years of his rule.
