The architects met on the occasion of the announcement of the procedure, which entails more than controversy regarding fees
The municipal tender for 16 gates opens the debate again about the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, during the heyday of the now-defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this municipality printed several pamphlets in support of Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What&#39;s more, it was accompanied by a numerical comparison with New York&#39;s Central Park.
After the CMB ceased to exist in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper limit of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that is not oriented on the axis north - south, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars instead of Yogi the bear.
This was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
Of course, the gate is more reminiscent of the idea of a park.
Either that or someone is trying to put a gate on the field.
So the only question arises: Collserola, a park or a mountain?
During the competition, both from a purely organizational point of view and based on reflection on the city, this question becomes the central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It&#39;s a theme as old as when two members of this old caste of the chosen shake hands when they meet in an elevator.
And it was this act that caused one of the rare coincidences between what the three Barcelona architects think and the leading university professors.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection procedure has its merits.
According to Roldán, after the issue of the bay side started, &quot;it is necessary&quot; to discuss the &quot;mountain side&quot; as well, so Ildefonso Cerdo&#39;s speech about green apples was not finished.
&quot;We have to start from the principle that the most extensive park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, its great availability.
Collserola is more complex&quot;, declared the architect, for whom the name &quot;gates to Collserola&quot; contains a &quot;lexicological trap&quot;: we must not imagine them &quot;as entrances to the park, but rather as defining zones where it is possible to act&quot;.
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the world of urbanism, qualifies the proposal as an &quot;intellectual challenge&quot; with &quot;some dangers&quot;.
The danger arising from the &quot;uncertainty that the public place project represents today&quot; after the experience of the 1980s, which had &quot;its swan song&quot; in the Forum area.
The first concern is the very demarcation of the boundaries where it should be built.
&quot;To define something means to take another step&quot;, that is, basically to move one step further.
&quot;The new urban planning and planning tools need to be kept in mind because the current ones (referring to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster&quot;.
If we focus on the question in more detail, Modol believes that the valley slope of Collserola can be &quot;considered a park&quot;, but the Barcelona part cannot, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work carried out by the Patronat de Collserola, which &quot;must not end up in the landfill&quot;, although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers his board to intervene in the project from &quot;the first moment&quot;.
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of pass that allows architects to join the debate, but he &quot;doubts&quot; that it should be this technical profile that will lead the multidisciplinary teams (&quot;it&#39;s all about skills&quot;, he adds) that need to be created: &quot;Architects should only be tools&quot;.
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the title to this game is complicated, because the tender documents lack the global vision of Collserol: &quot;16 tenders have been announced, all dealing with the mountain-sea axis, but there is no longitudinal study, which would look at the area and understand it as a whole&quot;.
This causes that at least he applied for all 16 tenders.
Otherwise, the project of one gate may conflict with the concept and definition of the architect of the neighboring gate.
In his opinion, the town hall should guarantee that the strip located immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should secure the entire length of the zone of equipment that would ensure a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino pardoned Jonás Larrazábal, who will be released
After 72 days in prison, Cadino Red&#39;s legal representative pardoned the brother of the mayor of Monterrey in a trial in which he was prosecuted for alleged extortion.
Manuel Jonás Larrazábal spent 72 days in prison and will now be released after Casino Red&#39;s legal representative granted him amnesty before the Second Criminal Court of the District, which was hearing a case of extortion in which the brother of the mayor of Monterrey was accused.
After the Casino Royale assassination, the owner of Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, published a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonás was supposed to ask him to pay an economic quota in order for Monterrey City Hall to allow an illegal operation in the betting house.
After the public indictment, the State Prosecutor&#39;s Office opened criminal proceedings against the brother of the Panist mayor. On September 2, he was detained and imprisoned for 30 days.
Then after spending 4 hours in front of the Public Ministry Agent number 3 for property crimes, he was transferred to prison 1, located in Barrio Antiguo in the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days after a second detention order was issued and a Public Service agent ruled out complicity or organized crime.
On October 19, he was taken to the Cadereyta Criminal Court on suspicion of extorting one and a half million pesos from the owners of Casino Red. However, he only stayed a few hours in a medium-security prison because he received death threats.
Officials allowed him to remain in the city cells in San Nicolás de los Garza during the trial.
On October 25, he was presented with an arrest warrant issued by the Secretary of the Second Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who declared that after nearly two months of investigation, enough evidence had been gathered to prove Jonás&#39;s guilt. The evidence includes, for example, the payment of 1.5 million pesos to casino officials in exchange for a promise to allow the operation.
This Monday, Casina Red&#39;s legal representative, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, appeared before Judge José Luis Pecin and asked for clemency for the brother of the regional mayor. Based on this, he will soon be able to return to freedom.
During the legal proceedings, the representative of the Public Ministry assigned to this court, Ramiro Arias, asked García Gómez if the damages had been repaired and which of the companions decided to grant the pardon. But the lawyer made it clear that the name will remain confidential.
On the basis of the official file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jonás Larrazábal. There will be no appeal possible in the trial that was conducted against him. It is also not possible to request compensation for damages or punishment.
After a discussion with the legal representative around 15:50, the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazábal Bretón.
The secretary of the court, Jorge Yanéz, arrived at the prison in the city of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonás that he had been granted an official pardon and his case had been placed on file.
He also informed him that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of the plane crash that killed the governor&#39;s secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven other people.
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the investigation into the accident that killed Secretary of the Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people show that the helicopter hit the terrain directly with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, said that before the plane took off, the pilot stated that the climatic conditions allowed the flight.
&quot;Parts emerging indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings became entangled in tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost the fuselage&quot;.
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, therefore it met all the requirements for transporting personnel.
Additionally, he stated that based on the investigation conducted in the impact area, no parts were found on the ground.
&quot;During the search, it was found that the parts of the plane were not located elsewhere, so the plane hit the ground as a whole.
&quot;The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all the requirements for transporting people.
The terrain has a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that the most important thing at the moment is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, stated that at the moment of impact the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was traveling at cruising speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
&quot;This information supports the hypothesis that it was a routine overflight operation at the time of the accident,&quot; he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jácome listed six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to visual flight rules, that is, the crew must be able to see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in AICM indicate adequate conditions at takeoff, accordingly the aircraft proceeds towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico there were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that because of the clouds, the crew was looking for a lower area and better visibility up to the Cuernavaca Valley.
Impact location.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the helicopter from the radar match, it is likely that there was no loss of control or violation of the flight path before the impact.
Dispersal of aircraft debris in a limited area:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A scatterplot of the aircraft debris indicates that the helicopter was intact at the time of impact with land.
No fire or explosion was reported.
No evidence of an explosion or fire was recorded at the scene of the accident.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been several contacts with land.
During field work, the remains of the plane were found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain slopes, the height of the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photos show footage of what is likely to be a breakup along the said route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search in the vicinity of the accident, in an area larger than the demarcation area, no remains of the helicopter were found, which strengthens the assumption that the impact occurred while the helicopter was still intact.
Mexico&#39;s Health Insurance Institute has begun research on the gene that causes obesity
The Health Insurance Institute is conducting research to discover the gene responsible for childhood and adolescent obesity. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to uncover the gene that causes obesity in children and young people. The research entitled &quot;Genetics of Obesity in Children and Adolescents&quot; will provide results related to overweight.
In the report, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Center of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been established.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without authorization, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in the Valle de México, where tests will be carried out on young people every Sunday from 8 am.
He emphasized that the research started in the Sports Center of Cuauhtémoc (Mexico State) and since October 8 this activity is also carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East of the State of Mexico).
Once data from 500 to 600 children have been obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics when it comes to the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years old, with parental consent and supervision, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He specified that every Saturday all participants are taken anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined and genes are examined (they try to identify genes that are involved in the formation childhood obesity).
Cruz López said this research reflects the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in children&#39;s weight.
&#39;Health surveys carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that in only six years there was an increase in obesity by 77% in boys and by 47% in girls. A dramatic increase also occurred in the case of overweight&#39;, said an expert from the IMSS.
He stated that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that a country&#39;s population differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Native American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the participants is that they will receive an overall assessment of the children&#39;s condition, which will determine if they exhibit any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
For now, the information is confidential, and doctors pass it on to parents in writing, explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order for their children to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle meaning a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the television all day and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Being overweight is also caused by high caloric intake, i.e. higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetic load, which is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in Asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, independent of climatic conditions and temperature
If paving was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200 thousand potholes after each rainy season in the Metropolitan Region of Valle de México, pointed out Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if construction and maintenance asphalt pavements were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or it would even be possible to eliminate them completely.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Potholes, which he delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should result in a mixture having similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low , so at high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight molecules called asphaltenes and low molecular weight ones called maltenes. Together, they give asphalt its typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the durability of asphalt in streets is not uniform, but changes throughout the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Between the uppermost layers is an asphalt insert, made of small pebbles embedded in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that makes up the liner is covered with asphalt.
When cars pass by or when pressure is created, it is thus possible for the forces in the pavement to be well distributed.
If it were modified asphalt, they would decompose even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the final layer, called the casing, is placed on top of the asphalt liner, consisting of fine stone, i.e. sand also embedded in the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with vehicle rims, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and must provide road friction.
Since it will be subjected to heavy loads as part of the paving, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken with the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, is also a very important factor to keep in mind. Water in particular has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt liner.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads in and it is difficult for it to get out, this causes the softening of all the layers of the paving and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that during the formation of potholes, the casing film is damaged first and then the asphalt liner is damaged. However, damage does not occur in one moment, but is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs with appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes, so the thickness of each individual layer of pavement must match the vehicle load and ensure that this load is not exceeded. This is the only way we can prevent the frequent occurrence of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and the research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow potholes to be easily repaired without having to use high temperatures.
What did the candidate from Valle lack to become the new Miss Colombia?
Analyzes of the factors that contributed to Melina Ramírez Serna not winning the Miss Colombia crown.
Valle thus wins the 14th title of the first multi-miss.
Valle del Cauca again fell short of the Miss Colombia crown.
Melina Ramírez Serna had to settle for being on the winner&#39;s podium, receiving a silver crown and sash, on the basis of which she became the new first multiple Miss Colombia.
Based on the results of yesterday&#39;s final in Cartagena, in which Miss Atlántico won and took the scepter, the aforementioned department won the 14th title of the first multi-miss. Melina thus joined the multitudes of women from Valle del Cauca who came within reach of the winning crown, but in the end were declared the first multi-misses. Among them are Miriam Ospina Benoit (1947), Clara Domínguez Borrero (1949), Patricia Bellini Ayala (1979), Lorena Álvarez (1981), Rose Mary Alzate (1983), Olga María Arenas (1987), Leila Blanque (1988), Mónica Evers (1989), María Consuela Pinedo (1990), Diana Isabel Romero (1993), Giselle Garcés Aljure (2000), Catalina Giraldo (2007), Stephanie Garcés Aljure (2008).
A question that many ask themselves. What was missing?
The result is the defeat of the big favorite, who showed in all the previous rounds that she has what it takes to become the new Miss Colombia, and not for nothing that she became the Queen of the Police and the Most Beautiful Face of Joile de Volgue. These titles were achieved by, for example, Taliana Vargas or Natalia Navarro, who subsequently took home the title of Miss Colombia.
One of the key factors that decided that the jury decided to name her only the First Multiple Miss is the fact that she did not convince with her answer to the question: &quot;Which book did you like the most and why?&quot;, asked by Martín Murillo Gómez of the literary editor Leamos.
The candidate answered the question:
&quot;I read a lot. I strongly believe in the role of literature, I believe that it is one of the forms of culturalization. The book that influenced me the most in my childhood was &quot;The Little Prince&quot;, a very deep book.
I am currently reading &quot;Crime and Punishment&quot;. It is a book that is part of the world literature that we should all know. And today I have with me a book by Irene Nemirovski, a Russian author. This is a wonderful book called &quot;El ardor de la sangre&quot;.
This answer was not liked, firstly because of the term &quot;culturalizing&quot; and secondly, because the candidate did not explain how the individual mentioned books made an impression on her.
After the ceremony, Melina declared that she was calm and happy with the result: &quot;The world is wise, what is meant to happen, will happen.
And you people, read if you can. The Little Prince is a wonderful book.”
One of the other hypotheses is that Valle destroyed the favorite positions.
A Bogotá journalist suggested that the fact that the candidate was the most popular, the most celebrated from the start and the one who had won all the previous awards (the Oster Gastronomic Challenge, the public title for the best artistic dress and the Queen Mother) aroused the envy of the other candidates, stressed the queen, who then she burned on stage.
It was evident during the first presentation of the swimwear on the Hilton beach and during the two parades before the final coronation.
Although she shone on both, it was clear that she lacked the power and passion that the representatives from Magdalena and Atlántico showed.
Ariel Osorio, journalist of the &quot;At Home&quot; program on Canal RCN, believes that the fact that Melinda won the title of the first multi-miss confirms the fact that the candidate who wins the most titles during the competition does not end up with the crown of the queen&quot;.
In addition, Valle has taken a rather unkind attitude towards the media in recent days, and this has not paid off for him.
Another hypothesis is that Valle failed to convince the jury of her interest in social work, which is the basis of the National Beauty Pageant.
On a side note, two days before the election, international jury member Lucy Doughty said they were looking for a woman who would be aware of the social needs of her country.
&quot;In the Miss Colombia competition, beauty alone is not enough, it is necessary to see something more than just physical beauty. It is necessary to focus on social feelings. It is important that the candidates are involved in such projects even before they enter the competition&quot;. she explained.
There is also speculation that candidate Valle lost points due to the shortcomings of her background and the fibrosis that was visible on her bottom. But this is completely contrary to the verdict of the jury, which chose her as Miss &quot;Natural Beauty&quot; for the healthiest body, proper nutrition and responsible physical activity.
Jorge Hernán Orozco, who prepares the queens, admits that Melina did not have the best body, that there were better girls, &quot;but the problems with the fibrosis on the bottom, which in my opinion was not very noticeable, took her points only on the last day&quot;.
Meanwhile, journalist Guido Hoyos of Cromos magazine believes the Valle native made a mistake by undergoing several surgeries.
&quot;Surgeries are fine, but they failed in Valle.
The body was never her strong point and here it took its toll&quot;.
Because of this award, which was given for the first time by the National Beauty Convention, after the swimsuit show there was a cruel prediction that came true. It was claimed that this was the satisfaction Raymundo gave Melina so that he would not have to give her the ultimate crown in the end.
Whether it is true or not, it is certain that today Melina began the year of her reign, not as a queen, but as a princess, from a position that gives her the opportunity to represent Colombia in various international competitions, where she will be named by the National Competition itself.
However, she will go down in history as one of the queens who, despite her thrilling success in Cartagena, did not reach the highest crown.
Such was the work of the Cali resident who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A fingerprint expert from Cali has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4th of last year, a fingerprint expert from CTI in Cali made history as the man who confirmed the identity of the Farc&#39;s supreme leader: &quot;Alfonso Can&quot; through fingerprint comparison.
Of the seven fingerprint experts who work in the CTI department, this week it was the turn of Eliazar González, a man from Puerta Tejada who has worked in forensic research for 21 years.
Early in his career, González worked at the town hall in Chocó, where he often had to spend more than five days trudging through the jungle to get to the location of the corpses that needed to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital city of Valle and, after completing the relevant courses, began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of skin friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week when the operation against the said Alfonso Can was carried out, Eliazar was told to take at least three days&#39; worth of clothing with him.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night, he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew he would have to identify two corpses and that he suspected one of them was the man who led the world&#39;s oldest guerrilla group. So they asked him to take the fingerprint card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the location where the corpse was found, he did not recognize him due to his physical appearance. He looked completely different than in the media.
He had no beard, dressed like a villager in the area, no glasses, much slimmer.
But prints don&#39;t lie.
Along with a galton magnifier, ink and transplanter, and light, Eliazar began comparing the corpse&#39;s dactyl records with the card entries.
The eye did not fail him: it was &quot;Alfonso Cano&quot;.
That same night, a man originally from Puerto Tejada was assigned to confirm to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, whether he was indeed the supreme commander of the Farc.
Searching for clues
For the typist from Sijín de Cali, the appreciation shown to Eliazar González by President Juan Manuel Santos at the press conference of the operative service against &quot;Can&quot; is very significant.
A lot of people don&#39;t know our work.
Fingerprinting is an exact science, with no margin for error, which can play a key role in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying corpses, these people help in the investigation of crimes such as theft or murder and confirm the identity of those caught.
When caught, many criminals present false documents or have no papers at all.
We take their fingerprints and look them up in the database.
The investigator said that in case of injury, he had to remove a piece of the wall of the house in the house, because in this place the thief leaned to take out the safe full of jewelry and money.
Walls are difficult because they are not designed to take fingerprints, but in this case we were able to get a print of the whole hand and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts&quot;, he recalled.
Fingerprints can also confirm or disprove suspicions in a murder case.
Not long ago, they found a dead man with bottles of alcohol around him.
Upon investigation, it was determined that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder, and indeed the print on the bottle confirmed this.
Although it cannot be 100% confirmed that he was indeed the murderer, it is clear that he appeared at the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprint expert explained that objects are &quot;rubbed with chemical or physical reactive agents.&quot;
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to collect them.
Then the fingerprints are sent to Asif, which is a database of offenders, or to the Registry.
&quot;The problem is that at the moment there are still many Colombians whose data is not entered anywhere&quot;, said the CTI expert.
He explained that not everything is as it appears on the CSI TV show.
Just as all that glitters is not gold, not everything you touch leaves a mark.
However, if it can be used, an appropriate comparison must be made.
&quot;Outrageous&quot; protest in New York
Hundreds of demonstrators crowded into Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to set up tents.
A large part of them waited for the order to clear the area and moved to a nearby park.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement provoked New York City officials on Tuesday as they sought a court order to re-enter the Manhattan square from which they were escorted out earlier in the day. They then tried to take over another New York park.
Hundreds of protesters crowded into Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to get there thanks to a court order allowing the &quot;outraged&quot; to return to camp on the site. A second part of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park in the north of the city, where further arrests took place.
&quot;If the court does not allow us to return to the square, we will settle elsewhere and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, both through rallies and peaceful demonstrations,&quot; said one of the spokespersons of the Occupy Wall Street movement, Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of the &quot;outraged&quot; to the eviction of the camp ordered by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg himself, went to court, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced eviction of the site and allowing the protesters to continue camping there.
In addition, another park located at the intersection of Central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, near the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and the parsonage property of Trinity Church were also occupied by &quot;outrages&quot;.
They managed to occupy the place for at least an hour, but then the police came and detained some of the protesters. Bray did not know the exact number, but said he saw some journalists being handcuffed as well.
The organization assures that several hundred people settled on the site. A delegation of religious leaders also came to show their support and also try to negotiate with the police.
Meanwhile, Piazza Zuccotti, which is a private property, remains closed. A court hearing is expected, which should take place on Tuesday, during which the legality of the morning evacuation should be analyzed.
Some of the displaced protesters even carried and distributed copies of the court order and even gave them to officers patrolling the square, causing &quot;some small clashes,&quot; said Bray, who condemned the fact that some police beat the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting members of the &quot;Occupy Wall Street&quot; movement or using &quot;laws that were published after the occupation began, or denying protesters access to a park with shops or other places they used to use.&quot;
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that due to this court order, the city has suspended the reopening of the public space and warned the protesters that local laws do not allow them to return the tents and sleeping bags.
The city&#39;s top official personally defended the early morning eviction of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which 200 people were detained and approached because the protesters were &quot;breaking the law&quot;.
Bloomberg explained that he ordered the evacuation of the square because it was becoming &quot;a place where people didn&#39;t go to protest, but to break laws and in some cases hurt others&quot; because &quot;some businesses had received threatening letters&quot; and &quot;neighbors were worried about their quality of life.&quot;
&quot;The morning evacuation was appalling and shows that Bloomberg is trying to maintain financial interests at the expense of the American working people,&quot; added a spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of &quot;not respecting freedom of expression.&quot;
Representatives of the Occupy Wall Street movement also said they planned to organize &quot;major events&quot; on Thursday in cooperation with community and union organizations to mark two months of protests. They started on September 17.
