Japan is coming back to life after a devastating earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to household consumption, thus ending the period of decline that began in March
Paralyzed since March last year, Japan&#39;s economy is now recovering from a devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster the country has faced since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Tokyo government put material losses at $300,000 million, a wound that is healing well despite the difficult global situation.
After three quarters of declines, the value of GDP between July and September was in such a position that it was possible to turn the page with definitive validity: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% annually.
The results of the second quarter - for Japanese people the tax year starts in March 2012 - also predict the greatest growth rate compared to the period January to March 2010.
The recovery can be partly explained by the purchase of machinery, which is necessary for the reconstruction of areas destroyed by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
Enterprises increased their investments by 1.1%, expenses will decrease by 0.9% compared to the period January to March. This is the first decline after six months of continuous growth.
However, the real awakening of the Japanese economy comes entirely from the impulse to use the crisis to emerge stronger or to restore infrastructure. It&#39;s about using scarcity to start from scratch.
Japan has woken up. Especially thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of Japan&#39;s GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, thanks to an increase in spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Flows have been handed to the internal market as the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the &quot;rescue assets&quot; for investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and worrying US forecasts. It is a privilege, but at the same time it is a great burden for export companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, which is a negative for a country whose economy is determined by the financial health of large technology groups.
For example, Toyota or Sony attributed their weak results in July to September precisely to the exchange rate of the yen.
While markets continue to besiege EU peripheral countries, Yoshihiko Noda&#39;s government is cautious.
&quot;We must pay attention to risks that persist, such as the destruction of some foreign economies, the impact of floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen,&quot; State Secretary for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa said yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) specified that most member countries showed clear signs of an economic slowdown in September.
An indicator that predicts stiffness in the world economy showed that the economies of major powers are slowing.
It fell by four tenths to 100.4 points from 100.8 in August.
The Eurozone even fell below the average, which is at the level of 100. It reached the level of 99.13 points.
