What constitutes unemployment fraud?
After the subsidies, the UMP party and the government launch an offensive against work incapacity.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be in Bordeaux on Tuesday 15 December and will visit the Social Assistance Office, where he will deliver a speech on the recurring theme since 2007 of the fight against social fraud and the redistribution of solidarity.
As an accompaniment to this offensive, which is based on the will to make savings in the context of increased austerity, but is no less clear from the point of view of the right-wing presidential campaign, the right-wing majority wants to focus on incapacity for work.
First, due to budget savings, the government intends to impose a fourth day of sick leave on private sector workers before they start taking sick pay.
To put it plainly, without the company&#39;s consent, an employee who falls ill would lose four days&#39; wages, i.e. at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that risks causing a lot of bad blood, but which, according to the newspaper Les Echos, could bring in 280 million euros.
And also a measure that would be accompanied by another measure of symbolic reach: to give civil servants one day of unpaid sick leave (so far they have no sick leave compared to three days in the private sector).
While these issues are the subject of discussion, the right-wing majority is also launching the topic of fraud, this time focused on malpractices linked to work incapacity.
&quot;The checks will be much more extensive and, in addition: if you are caught, you will return&quot;, warned Xavier Bertrand in an interview given to the station RTL on Sunday 13 November.
As in other cases, the effects of the notification seem somewhat disproportionate to the truth about disability wrongdoing.
These have in fact been subject to constant monitoring since 2002 and a political onslaught that has borne fruit.
The French are no more sick than elsewhere in Europe.
Let&#39;s stop at a few official numbers first.
According to the Caisse nationale d&#39;assurance maladie (CNAM - state health insurance company), in 2006 more than 237 million euros of daily benefits were paid out.
According to the French Institute for research and documentation in the health sector, in 2008, per diems, with their 11.3 billion euros, represented 5% of health expenditure.
Of this amount, 46% related to maternity allowances and occupational accidents and 54% related to incapacity for work, i.e. 6.2 billion euros.
That is, only 2.5% of healthcare costs.
According to a study by the Alma Consulting group, the French had an average of 14.5 days of sick leave in 2010, compared to 17.8 days in 2009.
An average that hides some variation: another survey published in 2007 on the jobs website Monster.com showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken a sick day.
Another study, this time conducted by health insurance institutions, specifies that in 2010, 37.8% of incapacity for work was less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to 1 month, 15% from 1 to three months and 11% took longer.
When compared with their European neighbours, French workers are no more prone to sick leave than elsewhere.
One long study carried out in 2010 by two CNRS (National Research Center) researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001 total absence (for health reasons or not) oscillated between 10% and 11.8% in France against 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in Great Britain and 18% in the Netherlands.
Cheating on sick leave represents only a very small part compared to undeclared work.
As far as scams go, these are only on a small scale.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 has meant that there are systematic checks aimed at work incapacity of more than 45 days.
In 2008, the CNAM stated that out of 1.5 million checks, 13.8% of the 285,000 carried out due to short-term incapacity were &quot;unauthorized or too long&quot;, i.e. 37,050 cases.
In the case of systematically checked incapacities longer than 45 days, 11% of cases of &quot;not adjusted or unauthorized&quot; were counted for 1.2 million checks, i.e. 132,000.
So a total of 169,000 &quot;unauthorized&quot; cases for several million employees who were unable to work.
A number that represents much less than the number representing work in the black.
According to UMP MP Dominique Tian, the author of a June report on the issue, this number would represent 9 to 15 billion euros missing in tax collection per year, i.e. more than the total amount of daily allowances and therefore infinitely more than the frauds associated with the latter.
