Euthanasia and assisted suicide should be legalized, says a commission of experts
Canadians are being denied death, according to a report by the Royal Society of Canada.
On palliative care, the commission urges governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to provide the best palliative care, including in cancer cases.
Canadian society lives by the idea of denying death.
Only 9% of Canadians actually accept the possibility of talking to a doctor about the conditions in which they want to die, and make decisions along those lines.
That&#39;s one of the conclusions of an extensive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts working in a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This commission recommends that the government amend the criminal law to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia where this choice appears necessary in a patient considered competent to make such a decision.
At the beginning, experts cite a recent poll by the independent agency Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
Although Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that &quot;the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to talk about death.&quot;
Medicalization yes or no, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts with the mandate of the Royal Canadian Society tell us.
And despite the desire to die at home, which most Canadians have, 68.6% of them die in a hospital.
This average is valid for all of Canada, while the province of Québec has the highest number with 86% of people dying in hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the report&#39;s authors reach conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already said it does not want to make any changes to the criminal law surrounding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
According to the experts, who also checked all the countries where these approaches are legalized or not considered a criminal case, there is no evidence that this decriminalization causes any abuses in the application, i.e. in the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on unauthorized or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, Mr. Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, confirmed yesterday during a teleconference more than numerous cases of these mistakes in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
&quot;Euthanasia is also carried out in Canada, where it is clearly illegal&quot;.
&quot;Assisted suicide is also done in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,&quot; explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians are pro-euthanasia
Recall that according to a survey conducted by the Angus Reid Forum in 2010, 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favor of euthanasia because they believe it will allow people at the end of life to ease their suffering.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not mean that we are sending the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled have less value.
When it comes to people who practice assisted suicide, 41% of the people interviewed believe that they should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or discontinuing a patient&#39;s care, the situation is less clear, the report&#39;s authors say.
Also in their list of recommendations, they suggest that the criminal law states that withdrawing from treatment for which there is a legally confirmed refusal is not a crime.
The expert commission also requires that medical professionals be educated on the duty to respect refusal of end-of-life treatment without fear of criminal prosecution.
On palliative care, the commission urges governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to provide the best palliative care, including in cancer cases.
Finally, in the case of palliative or terminal sedation, already widely used in Canadian health care facilities, the commission calls for it to be considered euthanasia when it no longer serves to reduce physical pain and subject to the same procedures.
Reservations of other experts
Some medical law experts have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the Royal Canadian Society&#39;s expert report.
Mr. Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in medical law, qualified the position of the experts-signatories of the report as &quot;extreme&quot; because, among other things, it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
&quot;This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 years old could ask to be helped to commit suicide&quot;, says Pierre Deschamps, who studied the résumé of the news yesterday.
P. Deschamps also underlines that it seems as if the authors of the report put the autonomy of the person above all other values that shape the social fabric of society.
For &quot;in society, he says, there are warning signs and restrictions&quot;.
Medical law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed &quot;strong objections to the conclusions of the report, which she described as a &#39;manifesto for euthanasia&#39;&quot;.
Margaret Somerville, herself a Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada, is particularly skeptical of the report&#39;s data regarding the absence of wrongdoing in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, i.e. the Netherlands and the US state of Oregon.
