Energy policy:
facts must prevail over dogmas
If there&#39;s any topic that can&#39;t be captured on short-term balance sheets or emotion, it&#39;s energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is only natural that the election meeting should be an opportunity to think about such investments and the place that nuclear power occupies.
The debate will only be successful if all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options are explored.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
There are currently 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic developments will cause the demand for electricity to double between now and 2050, if we do not want to deprive a significant part of the world&#39;s population of important parts of life.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be faced in order to continue to generate electricity, and we cannot forget the imperative to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a topic that is currently disappearing from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not affect any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
But this is not the case in Belgium, which subordinates its decision to the need to find some other source capable of replacing itself, nor in Switzerland, which considers it correct to build only the latest generation power plants.
On the contrary, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name at least some countries, continue with their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its park by one unit by resuming the construction of one plant suspended after the Three Mile Island plant accident.
If the German model based on renewable energies is sometimes presented as an example, the reality contradicts this.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, and a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal power plants.
We will feel all these unpleasant effects within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European wind power champion, from which it takes 30% of its electricity, is also one of the biggest consumers of coal and gas due to the irregularity of the wind, causing CO2 emissions and Danish electricity prices to be 65% and 65% higher respectively. 50% than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbors will pay an electricity bill 40% higher than what French households pay.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy represents a key factor in competitiveness and the guarantee of maintaining industry on national territory, French businesses enjoy the benefits of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would cause a sharp increase in the price of electricity, rendering illusory the beautiful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that the vast majority of the French refuse to pay, just as they are not fundamentally opposed to this energy, as opinion polls show.
