Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - the overloading of the police, the courts and the administration subjected to the politics of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the status of the &quot;country of human rights&quot; that France boasts of.
More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that became topical when the Minister of the Interior (see Libération of May 23) declared that France &quot;does not need foreign talent, masons and waitresses&quot;.
But so far, it has rarely been discussed from an economic perspective.
It must be said that there is a fairly broad agreement between the left and the right in this area.
On the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone in 1976 when he declared that &quot;900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with 2 million immigrant workers&quot; and on the left, Michel Rocard, when he said in 1990 that France &quot;cannot accept all the misery of the world &quot;.
The only difference is the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of hordes of Polish plumbers on French territory was shared on the right and left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity we deign to extend to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande limits himself to banalities when he states that common development will make it possible to solve our &quot;migration problem&quot;.
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may be valid in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in their recently published work synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.): there is a wide consensus on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages and employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration cripples growth and hurts employment.
Concerns about the impact caused by migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially the less skilled ones, and create downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are much more complements than substitutes for French workers by doing jobs in sectors with a shortage of workers.
Low-skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where education is not enough to supply jobs.
Positive impact on wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anesthetists, these additions between French and migrants make the arrival of immigrants have a positive effect on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements will cause a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And it does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries, averaging 1% of the total budget.
The World Labor Organization, for example, estimates that in Germany, one gray-haired immigrant at the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (revenues minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy expressed his desire to fight for the missing percentages of growth &quot;with bare teeth&quot;.
The aforementioned teeth used to repel immigrants had just the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a rare and also a very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, after all, despite the fact that it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it experienced during the XX. century, the tragedy of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, gulags, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some people may have believed that for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it would be enough to make an election, and make it as direct as possible.
However, it has been known since Napoleon that it was about ease of thinking.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become an &quot;instrument of oppression&quot; as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, departmental organization and control of power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just that and from the beginning a crisis of politics and democracy.
Admitting the error of the Greek yes-no referendum will in this respect have the value of a double revelation: revealing the necessity of a great return of political power, but also revealing the disturbing sense of its impossibility, its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence must be thought through in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the Democratic struggle have shifted today and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer firing in the right direction.
There is nothing to be gained if we demand a series of national referendums conducted on a case-by-case basis and in a disorganized manner.
Blank exposed to a European absolutist monarch or leap with bound feet into the emptiness of the nationalist abyss: what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a joint, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we wouldn&#39;t even know where to stop the list - because the crisis is in Europe.
Indeed, it is the whole of Europe bowing to the dictates of the markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its incompetence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We worry about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its peoples.
There is an urgent need to return the governance of the European project of democratic sovereignty.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, get rid of the rule of the markets and prepare the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will presuppose decisions at the European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise it would lead us to disaster.
After we have fought for a long time against this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, today everyone is strongly demanding a European economic government.
So be it.
But to think it without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
In order to establish a republic in France, it was necessary to &quot;be&quot; republicans.
A revolution in interests could not be enough for this.
This lesson still applies.
We must build a Europe that is more economically integrated.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic Europe and a true European democratic sovereignty.
Let&#39;s become Europeans to build Europe.
