All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom executives present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an important technical feat.
The submarine pipeline is made of steel with a concrete jacket to protect it from the anchors of marine vessels.
It rests on the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
&quot;Nearly a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed for safety reasons,&quot; says Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipeline itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted anywhere along its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
One inspection platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it as the Swedes were less than eager to see a Russian state-owned company set up permanently off their coast.
&quot;In the event of a fault, we stop the flow of gas in less than 1 minute&quot;, explains Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, because the welds were designed so that a leak would occur once every 100,000 years.
The outside of the pipeline is inspected by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is inspected by equipment that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the destination, after the entire three-day journey at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains Gazprom, which holds a share of 51%.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, tasked with building and operating the pipeline.
The company is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely favorable.
Gazprom subsequently leased all its gas transportation capacities to this company for a five-year, renewable contract.
&quot;Gazprom will make a profit from the total capacity, no matter what the amount of gas actually transported&quot;, explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez group, investment costs thus rose to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be recouped, since only Gazprom bears the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas exit gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 6 million.
Moleskine - branded notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded fifty years ago, wants to provide the joy of writing again.
It brings the scent of adventure, of hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its leaves of a faded white color that seems to have aged over time.
After all, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born already in 1997.
At that time, the Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decides to launch a new designer but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes on the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique &quot;moleskin&quot; (imitation leather), which is used, for example, to modify the surface of benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
&quot;Moleskine brought back to popularity an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,&quot; says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales rose 26% to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is far removed from the secret production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to construct an artificial portrait of the buyer, as the notebook will attract the businessman as well as the student or professional.
The image of the Moleskine notebook belongs to the fact that its owners are cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded people.
The small Italian company, which in its beginnings had 12 employees, today has almost a hundred and since 2008 has had two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notebooks to bookstores and, through the FNAC chain of stores, to small boutiques in city centers, where he has been able to assert his identity.
&quot;We followed the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, through the stormy development of emails&quot;, explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition &quot;Walk&quot;, where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
It also launched new leopard-like notebook boards in August at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine profits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, notebook cases... The brand expands to a whole range of carriers.
A success that aroused envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment funds SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the proportion of unemployed disabled workers so high?
Around 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Handicapped opens today.
Despite the voluntarist public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed disabled persons is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it daunting?
&quot;No, underlines Éric Blanchet, general director of the Adapt association, which organizes the Week for the employment of the disabled.&quot;
&quot;The progress made in 15 years is remarkable.&quot;
&quot;At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher.&quot;
&quot;However, much remains to be done.&quot;
It must be said that there are still numerous obstacles for unemployed disabled people before they start working.
These are elderly people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% do not have a high school diploma and only 10,000 are disabled out of 2.3 million university students.
And finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria that make returning to work particularly difficult, and which represent &quot;the heart of the problem&quot;, according to Christian Grapin, CEO of the association Tremplin, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses hire disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
It remains unspoken, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that interviewed managers had a &quot;poor level of knowledge about disabled people&quot; with &quot;an exaggerated idea of people in wheelchairs and psychological or mental deficiencies&quot;.
As a result, private businesses with more than 20 employees are still far from meeting the 1987 law&#39;s goal of employing 6% of disabled workers.
The last known figures, which come from 2008, indicate a state equal to 2.6%.
&quot;Now we&#39;re around 3%,&quot; says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization tasked with collecting fees from businesses that don&#39;t comply with the law.
The proof is the number of &quot;fined&quot; companies, as well as the amounts paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 guilty companies to 46,000 (from 606 to 480 million euros).
&quot;The 2005 law that increased contributions created a strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc.&quot;
&quot;But this improvement also demonstrates a real awareness, especially in large enterprises.&quot;
According to the Department of Labor, only 59% of businesses with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of businesses with 100 to 199 employees.
